Date: Thu, 23 Jun 88 17:36 EST
From: MALICE@ISIS.MIT.EDU
Subject: cooking and camping

Bread:	Try commercially available Scandinavian knackbrod or Wasa crip 
bread--contains no water, won't go stale.
	Try some of the recipies in Sir Kenelm Digby's Closet Opened(1651) or 
traditional welsh or irish recipies containing lots of fruit (like 30 to 50 %)
	In general, bread with no eggs, milk, or butter will go stale faster, 
but enriched breads will mold sooner--take your pick.
	What the scots did was carry along whole oats and small flour mills 
and make fresh oatcakes on griddles.  The whole grain didn't spoil and they 
needed no ovens.  Ive had fresh oat cakes but havn't managed the knack of 
making them.  They are available commercially, although they don't taste quite 
the same.

Noodles: You Bet!!
	Vermicelli is 15th c if not earlier cooked in either good broth and 
served with cheese or in water and served with sugar and spices
	Tortelini are also period under the name of Tarteletts.  (actually the 
fillings would have been different, different spices, probably currents added) 
You can buy them dry in boxes.

Meats:	In Cariodoc & Elizabeth's Medieval Miscellany you will find something 
called (i believe) "gentry salt"  It's a mixture of spices and breadcrumbs to 
be used along with vinegar (at least 5% acidity) to preserve cooked fowl. 
(duck is nice)  It's good as a side dish or condement, but i wouldn't want it 
as a meal unless is were washed and cooked into something.

Cheeze and eggs:	We had good succes making these last even at room 
temperature by dipping them in wax.  try wrapping a meal's worth of chese in a 
bit of *cotton* (not that gastly synthetic stuff they foist on one under the 
same name) chese cloth and covering it with melted parafin.  it discourages 
mold and keeps the water from the cooler out.

One other technique:	Try making a lot of something that is period and tasty 
and that you know will keep.  Then go up to a group that is camping and eating 
together and say, "I have more x than i can use, can i trade it for some of 
your y?" and if the cooks have (as they often do) grossly overestimated the 
ammount of food they needed you are likely to get a meal and some good 
conversation to go with it.

