Date: Fri, 24 Jun 88 12:14:45 EDT
From: akobayas@spica2.mit.edu (Andrew Kobayashi)
Message-Id: <8806241614.AA13680@spica2.prime.com>
Subject: Fighting Blow Strength

This is a topic that always troubles me when it comes up, because what we
are trying to do is legislate morality, and that never works well.  The
reason that there are problems with calibration levels in the lists is
because, with present technology, there is no objective way to judge the
strength of a blow "from the outside", and that judgement must therefore
be left to the individual being struck.  The judgment is necessarily
subjective, and the perception of the blow is influenced by many things.

One problem is that different fighters fight for different reasons,
and with many different attitudes.  Someone who is out for the sport and is
a fan of good technique will "die" much more willingly than someone who
is consumed by winning.  There is the belief that different tourneys require
different calibration levels, so that a blow that might have "killed" in a
Baronial Champion tourney won't cut the mustard in Crown.  Many members of
the Chivalry feel silly being "killed" by unbelted fighters, and allow this
to color their judgement.  The list is endless.

This variety is the chief problem i have with the "too heavy, my lord" call.
Here we have proven ourselves completely unable to judge one threshhold of
blow satisfactorily; how much worse will it be if there are two?  As things
stand the Marshals can intervene and enforce an "obvious" kill.  With a
fighter able to ignore blows that are too heavy, even this infrequently-used
tool would be taken away.  It also allows fighters to define the range of
blows themselves; the same people who abuse the system now will continue to
do so.  My mind boggles at the spectacle of a three-hour final bout at Crown,
with each blow struck alternately too heavy and too light as the finalists
search delicately for that "just right" blow that will fell the opponent.

Also, anything that requires fighters to think more is probably moot anyway.
:-)

I think the Lady Malice is on the right track with her observation on the
concept of a "killing" blow.  Combat in the SCA is an organized spectator
sport.  We don't really die, we're in it for the fun.  I personally take
lighter blows than many, frequently just because the blow was pretty and
"ought" to have worked.  (Also i don't like getting mashed to a pulp.  :-)
We are not trying to hurt each other, we are demonstrating physical prowess
in a particular area.

I am not in favor of going to a judged system such as is used in saber,
though.  There should be some "reasonable" minimum blow strength, or the
fighting will quickly degenerate into something very much like fencing. :-)
The weapons that we are modeling have mass and behave in certain ways
because they do, and we must not lose that.

The above is mostly addressed to the fighters among you; how about the rest?
Non-fighters should take an interest in fighting so that the fighters have
some other points of reference for behavior.  If nothing else each local
group should be very careful in choosing its Knight Marshal, for it is very
likely that the trainees will turn out very much like the trainer.  If your
KM is turing out robot-like stick jocks *and you don't like that*, complain
to your Seneschal.  (Seneschals *love* input.  Just ask them.  :-)  Of course
for this to make a difference there will have to be a willing right-thinking
individual in the wings to propose as an alternative, but at least the powers
that might as well be will be aware that there *is* a problem.

Enough for now.

Master Kobayashi Yutaka
Carolingia/The East

