Greetings Lady Orianna. I'd just like to comment on the differences between
your Sergeant's and Yeoman's Tourney and ours.

Here in An Tir most (all?) of the baronesses sponsor a yearly Tourney to
allow those interested to earn a Sergeant's or Yeoman's belt. This is
not a "top score gets the belt" competition, but more of a personal
challange to score well overall. Several or no belts may be given out.
(Last year 5 Sergeants and 1 Yeoman were make in Lions Gate.)

The areas of testing are very similar - fighting/archery, strategy &
tactics, heraldry, games, dance, bardic skill, and chivalry. Each applicant
is required to submit a letter of application, done by his/her own hand.
(I say "done" rather than "calligraphed" because last year Baroness Amanda
received an application tooled in leather; and the year before one that was
carved in wood.)

Chivalry is judged by all of the ladies present at the event and covers the
applicant's behaviour over the previous year.

One very important item that you didn't mention was the responsibilities
of the S and Y toward their Baroness. A new S or Y swears fealty to his
Baroness and promises to protect and defend her and the Barony against all
comers. There are "Sergeants Against the World" battles at kingdom events,
a "Baronesses Chess Tournament" where the S&Y give their advice and when a
Sergeant makes Knight, he must first ask his Baroness to release him. 
Somewhat serious stuff, but a S/Y is very proud to wear his belt (with
the identifying baronial buckle).

