I darn near fell off my chair laughing at this.  There is a definite
need in both mundane and SCA life not to take oneself too seriously.
This good gentle (he is a good gentle, I've met him) stated that 
he grew up in a traditional Scots household.  He appreciates the pipes.
I think he has a right to poke a bit of fun at his own culture.  from
the point of view of a very small mundane child, seeing a Scotsman
for the first time in full array with pipes is a highly unusual thing
(small Child, not just small boy). I will take occasional humorous pot
shots at my own activities, or activities of groups I am involved with,
not ever meaning to insult.  Saying 'I'm dressing up in a tin can and 
beating people over the head with sticks' is not an insult to fighters,
but an indication that I'm not getting solemn and stodgy about an
activity I joined because it was fun.  There must be tremendous personal
satisfaction (which can be loosely translated as fun) in mastering such
a difficult instrument as the bagpipes, or people wouldn't spend so
many years perfecting their skill with them.  I understand that many
people, maybe even many SCA people, do not like ANY bagpipes, and they
do make rude comments about what they don't understand.  I find it a 
true joy to be able to dance to the music of a gifted piper, but I'm 
certainly not going to be somber and solemn about it;  Traditional 
reels and step-dances are some of the most light-hearted and cheerful
music of any historical period, and I find the Scots culture to be 
much more fun-loving than the Normans, for example.  This is probably 
why so many SCA folk take Scottish and Irish personas.  
   OK, maybe Aaron should have included a smiley, but he meant no hurt.
I am saying this because I too poke fun at myself and the SCA, and 
could have posted the same thing.  We can retain our respect for the 
talents and effort we put forth, but if we start taking ourselves too
seriously, this wonderful little universe we call the current middle ages
won't be any fun anymore.   

