Subject: Athol Brose

Oh, wow!  Athol Brose!  Alcoholic oatmeal, my favourite!

For those who have no idea what we're talking about, here's my own (quite
successful, I might add) recipe:
2 c rolled oats (these should not be quick-cooking; I've never tried it 
with McCann's Irish, which are steel-cut oats, but it might be worth an 
experiment...)
2 c cold water
1 pt. heavy cream
1 pt. good Scots Whisky (don't waste a single malt on this unless you want
to be really extravagant, in which case I recommend Glenfiddich -- the Islay
malts, like Laphroaig (my favourite), are really too strong for this.  Drink
them straight and unadulterated, as the good Lord (and I'm not telling which
one <grin>) intended).

Put the water to the oatmeal.  Let the mess sit overnight.  In the 
morning, strain out the oat water and wring the remaining mash through a
cheescloth (I like to let some of the "pulp" get into the water).  The
oat water should be almost silky in texture.  Then add the cream and
whisky, and honey to taste (start with about 1/4c).  Shake it all up,
and let it sit in the fridge for another day or so, for all the
flavours to marry.  It's a good idea to keep it out of the sun at
tourneys, but I've found it doesn't really need chilling (in fact, it
tastes better at just cooler than room temp, or even room temp) --
probably all that lovely high-test Scotch... <grin>

Enjoy, and as the Scots say, "Slainte mhaith" (pron. slan-che vah).

Yours in Barleycorn,
