Bayleaf repels ants and most crawly bugs, and is definitely in period.  
Other repellants (but ones that might flavor food!) would be cedar shavings or 
pennyroyal oil or herb.  To keep bread in a closed box (i.e. not a basket, 
which has air circulation), be sure to put some variety of clean rushes or 
porous paper in the bottom, separated by a trivet from the bread.  The rushes 
or paper will absorb excess moisture (keeping the bread from getting soggy as 
the heat drives out some of its moisture), and the trivet will keep the rushes 
from sticking to the bread.  Another alternative to this is heavy waxed paper, 
which is not quite the equivalent of the oil-paper that I think goes back this 
far, but is probably more aesthetic than plastic.  Oil cloth (oiled canvas, 
with an oil that is edible but not easily gone rancid) will also do for many 
things.  These will make your food a little soggy if it has any moisture to 
it.

If you are hanging things from trees et al, dip a portion of the rope in 
pennyroyal oil to keep bugs from crawling down the rope onto your food.

  >  Not only are coolers definitely
  >  out of period, but food stored in them has a very great chance
  >  of being soaked.
  >  
Food in coolers can also be put in oilcloth or up on some sort of trivet 
arrangement.  Ice can be frozen in crockery, also.  Coolers may not be period, 
but on the other hand, food poisoning is...

  >  I got rather tired of the summer-sausage/whole-wheat-roll diet over
  >  the weekend.  Fortunately I did have some fruit, and we did have
  >  a feast saturday night, but the rolls just didn't cut it very well.
