If you want to have bread keep, here are some options:
	Make flatbread (no yeast)  (this is like putting it out in the
		sun to begin with...:-)
	Don't use milk or eggs, but use more oil than usual
	Look into receipts for hard crusted breads, like pumpernickel, and
		make round loaves only big enough for one meal (no exposed
		cut sides).  Bake the bread on a porous surface (unglazed
		ceramic, such as you can get for pizza, or a board--not 
		PINE!) to get a good bottom crust.  If you have neither,
		then halfway through baking (when the bread is fairly well
		"set,") put the bread up on a baking rack.  Hope you have good
		teeth!

  >  Something which would be nice 
  >  is breads/fruits/meat-dishes which can be cooked up in advance and 
  >  transported into the place.
  >  
Try the book "Putting Things By" (forget the author's name--apologies).  This 
will tell you how to do nifty things like waterglass eggs (don't know if this 
is period...).

I'd recommend hitting your local backpacking store or outing club and look 
into "trail cooking."  The ingredients tend to be simple staples that keep 
well (and most things are period or late period--potatoes, tomatoes and corn 
are rampant...).  Cured meats are often well prepared in stews with dried 
fruit.  Most things will not ship once cooked, since it is their lack of 
moisture or concentration of sugar or salt which keeps them preserved.

Also remember that water is easy to boil, which means that you have a variety 
of noodles and noodle sauces (many of which can be kept well in jars or 
reconstituted or made simply and fresh).  Eat your bread early on, and then 
move on to your stores of pasta and grains.

Let's face it.  Trail cooking gets monotonous fast, but fasting is even more 
monotonous.  Trail cooking IN PERIOD is worse.
