Date: Wed, 22 Jun 88 12:08:33 EDT
From: almond%hustat@harvard.harvard.edu (Russell Almond)
Subject: Re: Camping Considerations


A few suggestions to help your camping efforts.  First, it sounds like
your eating area is not covered by any kind of tarp or pavillion.
This is a sound investment because, only one person in your camping
group need make it, and it will keep the sun off of you during the
day, giving you a shady place to eat, relax, and store food.

Second, buy yourself a parasol.  It will keep the sun off of you while
you are watching battles and shopping.  (It also can be used to keep
the sun off of that special lady, but only if she stands real close).
Also, drink half-strength Gatorade.  The rule (as they teach to
waterbearers) is, if you can't taste the electrolites, you better have
some more.  I also might suggest a midday bath or shower (as was done
in civilized country, but not by the Frankish barbarians).  And make
sure your clothes are loose fitting and breath well.

Third, you may want to use an cooler, even though it is not period.
Remember, you do not have the option of slaughtering animals on
premisis.  Disguising it may be nice, but each campsite has its own
level of authenticity, and ultimately it is your own standards you
must meet.  I also use a gas stove to cook, because with 5000 people
packed into Cooper's lake, not everyone can build a firepit.  In
period people would have used charcoal for cooking rather than open
fires for the most part anyway.  A small charcoal grill can be bought
inexpensively.  Last of all, although there is a large psycological
barrier to leaving the War to go into town, Butler is only 10 miles
away, and has grocery store, department stores, and all kinds of other
modern conveniences.  If your staying the week, you can always plan to
make one trip out to restock perishable commodities.

Best of luck putting your camp together, and I hope to see you,
Inshallah, at the War.

	--Mustapha
