Greetings!

"An Exaltation of Lark, or The Venereal Game", by James Lipton, 2nd
edition, was published by Penguin Books, 1977, and reprinted in 1987.
ISBN 0 14 00.4536 8, for those of you fascinated by such things.  Any
decent bookstore should be able to order it in.

Just a brief sampling of the more delightful period terms lsited
therein:

A Superfluity of Nuns
A Draught of Bottlers
A Neverthriving of Jugglers
A Melody of Harpists
An Example of Masters (!)
A Scolding of Seamtresses
A Disworship of Scots
A Dignitity of Canons
A Charge of Curates
A Discretion of Priests
A Skulk of Friars
An Abominable Sight of Monks


A period term for Knights is A Route of Knights, from the Old French
Route, meaning a troop or throng.  However, I prefer a Chain of
Knights, or A Bashing of Knights. 

For Laurels, depending on one's point of view:  A Wreath of Laurels, A
Branch of Laurels, A Pomposity of Laurels, A Stitch of Laurels, A
Snitch of Laurels, A Snip of Laurels, A Snipe of Laurels, etc.

For Pelicans: A Weight of Pelicans (or even A Hundredweight of
Pelicans), A Flock of Pelicans, A Service of Pelicans, or (for those
of you with peerophobia) A Disservice of Pelicans.

Any SCAdian order has at one time of another been, for example, A
Disorder of Silver Crescents.

A Staff of Marshalls
A Gawk of Mundanes
A Bored of Directors
A Flurry of Ladies-in-Waiting


Enough for now.

