Date: Tue, 21 Jun 88 11:24:57 EDT
Message-Id: <8806211524.AA02924@flume.dec.com>
From: curtis%lyceum.enet@decwrl.dec.com (Dick 'Aristotle' Curtis)
Subject: Various styles of "set and turn single"

-- In reply to Dani's questions about "Set and Turn Single" --

	SET PEDANT


In Carolingia, the standard was that each dancer would step left and then
right (pretty much a single step, quite flat), and turn CCW in a small circle.
That's the local SCAdian style, courtesy of Baron Patri and Dr. Brainard's
reconstructions;  I think that you can find other groups in New England
following the style of Cecil Sharp and the Country Dance Society.

The Country Dance Society dancers go right, then left, then turn CW in
a small circle, and (it's been a while) I think that most of them do the
syncopated 3-steps-in-two-beats style.  In most instances, this is done
either along or across the set;  however, there are some English Country
dances (I think that Lilliburlero [1686] is one, but don't have my Playford
handy to check), and Scottish Country dances as well, that have a "progressive
set", which you have seen, in which the dancers make their sets at a 45-degree
angle to the direction in which they are proceeding (towards the other dancer,
who in some dances is their partner, and in some dances may be their corner).

I'm hardly an expert on the Scottish Country Dance, as I normally try it
only once a year, at the New England Folk Festival;  what I recall of it
is that it too is syncopated, as a small-single+change-weight+small-kick-to-
pointe (easier, and more pleasant, to do than to describe).

If you go to New England contradances (which are a lot of fun for newcomers,
and become more fun with practice), you will find people doing the step-and-
kick style, in what's called a "balance";  the standard is to step towards
your partner, then away, because the following figure usually brings you
towards your partner (the commonest figure to follow a balance is a swing.
If you have never done this, you are indeed missing something wonderful, and
in the public interest I will volunteer to teach it [outside of SCA happenings]
to interested people, particularly ladies (-:  End of public service
announcement.)

The method Dani describes, in which both dancers move in the same direction,
on opposite feet, sounds to me to be somewhat less flirtatious than if they
move away, then towards, then turn away from their partner.  My (not-overly-
educated) opinion of the hand-holding is that holding hands for the set
itself might work, but holding hands for the turn single would give the
dance a significantly different (and more inappropriately modern) flavor.
I'd assume that most (if not all) of the dancers would have similar feelings,
though, and wouldn't do that.

Also, I would recommend trying "Rufty Tufty" first using a turn-in-place,
and then a turn-in-a-small-circle;  for that dance (if I haven't confused
it with "Heartsease") I think that you'll find one clearly superior to the
other.

As for the old question "which way does it start?", I've no good answer.
I vaguely remember hearing something (which I think may have been attributed
to Baron Patri, to the effect that there was a switching of starting
directions (and feet) during the eighteenth century, from the left to the
right.  I've also heard the assertion that people in the Middle Ages (and
maybe the Renaissance as well) would go to the right, or clockwise, as they
would consider the other direction to be unlucky.  (Something about going
against the sun's direction was supposed to be unlucky.)  Finally, there is
an interesting difference between the SCAdian and CSharp reconstructions of
siding:  the SCAdian (locally) is to make a small double left ("side LEFT"),
to meet brushing right shoulders, and a double back on the right foot;  the
CDS style ("J-siding") is to make a double and turn half to face back, and
a double and turn back to place -- but as they brush RIGHT shoulders, they
call it "siding RIGHT"!  In the absence here (in my office) of reference works
and time to research, I wonder if there might be some lack of consistency
across primary sources, as to whether a direction refers to the feet or hands,
or to one for some figures and the other for others.

I should add that the differences in style between the local SCAdians and
the CDS has caused me embarrassment on more than one occasion, while I was
trying to get used to such differences.  At an English dance at the NEFF,
it was politely pointed out to me that I had all the moves down, but as
mirror images!  It might be well to keep this in mind, in groups which have
people who have experience with non-SCA English Country Dance.

	CLEAR PEDANT


	Please excuse me while I resume my aestivation.

In service (once and future),
Aristotle Herakleides (Dick CURTIS%LYCEUM.DEC@DECWRL.DEC.COM)



