Message-Id: <8806211032.AA00994@davids.UUCP>

Having just returned from a camping event (Border Raids) I have
a couple of questions which have occurred to me that I'd like
to have opinions on.

These are questions which "ought" to be covered in the varied
introductory texts (i.e. Knowne World Handbook and that ilk),
but which I have not been able to find covered in such texts.

First is storage and types of food.  We had a couple of problems
with our food over the weekend.  The worst was the ants that found
their way into the loaf of bread which was wrapped in plastic,
and the other loaf of bread that dried out completely because it'd
been left in the sun.  

While leaving bread in the sun is a silly thing to do there ought
to be something better to do.  Like storing it in some sort of
box, one which it wouldn't matter if it were left in the sun or 
not and one which is proof from the various and sundry beasties
lurking about.  A wicker basket type thing would serve for keeping
the sun off but not for keeping beasties out.  (A related problem
was the ants which found the outsides of the honey jars, something
which would draw ants into a wicker basket even if a loaf of bread
would not).  Can wooden boxes be made to be safe from beasties?

One desire of mine is to keep the solution at least somewhat period
if not totally period.  Encasing everything in silvery plastic
is not the proper solution :-), even though it is a very good solution
for many purposes.  Something else which bothers me (but I still use)
is the predominance of coolers.  Not only are coolers definitely
out of period, but food stored in them has a very great chance
of being soaked.

Is there an herb which is repellant to beasties but is safe to eat?
That would be a nice solution if there were...  The herb book I
have -- while it is an otherwise wonderful-seaming book -- does
not cover herbs for non-perfume/cooking/health uses.

I got rather tired of the summer-sausage/whole-wheat-roll diet over
the weekend.  Fortunately I did have some fruit, and we did have
a feast saturday night, but the rolls just didn't cut it very well.

I am thinking ahead to the war.  We'll be attending for the whole
week this year and I'm rather worried along these lines.  I can
cook on a campfire -- I'm not *that* addicted to my roomates
microwave :-) -- but prefer not to.  Something which would be nice 
is breads/fruits/meat-dishes which can be cooked up in advance and 
transported into the place.

All of these are period concerns as well as modern concerns, so
surely there are solutions.  I would be interested in hearing others'
solutions.

Second is what to do about heat problems.  This last weekend was
very hot and very dry.  I thought I did all the proper things to
make sure I didn't have any heat problems, but ended up with
an horrocious headache and feeling "woozy" during our feast and
ended up not doing *any* of the revelling which I really wanted
to take part in :-).  (Not to mention the lady I'd been talking
to all day .... sigh ... ).

I was drinking water all day long (enough that I was passing water
normally).  I ate one or two ounces of beef jerky (high in salt).  
As I said above, I had whole-wheat rolls, peaches, sausage, cheese 
for breakfast & lunch.  The only bad thing I did was to have share 
some cheap Italian wine with the lady I mentioned.  (About 2 "drinks" 
worth).  This was around dinner time just before court.  I had had 
weak head pains all day long, but they did not start in earnest 
until evening/court.  I think I may have stopped drinking water after I had 
that wine, but I'm not sure.  Also, I wore a headpiece all day long
made from a circlet holding down a a piece of light yellow linen.
The circlet itself does not press against my skull, but that day I
wore the linen a little differently -- two layers between the circlet
and my skull instead of one.  It eventually was uncomfortable and
I switched back to one layer.  The last thing is that I'm not a fighter,
but I did spend a fair bit of time in the sun watching fights and
visiting the merchants.  This includes a late afternoon stroll through
the merchant area and the two bridge battles.  (3-5 PM).

Am I doing reasonable things?  Can someone recommend a book/article to
read regarding heat?  Again this is something which isn't covered well
in the KWH (and the like).  The relavent article in the KWH covers
the next stage or two beyond where I was.

I would really *love* to be able to enjoy a court for once.  It seems
that for some reason by the time court comes around I am always out
of it in some way or another.  Either these heat problems, or like
at Harvest Day last fall when court wasn't held until very very late
and I was very much out of it and still had to drive back to Lexington
that night.

Oh.  And if you get the impression that I had a bad weekend -- well
I didn't.  It was a good event ('twould have been better if there'd
been some place to park the cars OTHER THAN ***IN*** THE CAMPSITES)
and we had a lot of fun.  There were two memorable things.  The first
was the investment of the Baron Flame.  The Flame has existed for
some really long time (as a Barony) but has never had a Baron.  Now
it does.  The *really* memorable part was the chant which was sung
while the people of the Barony (as well as the people of Dragonsmark,
my shire) processed down to the "stage" (what's the right term?).
If I can manage it I'll get a copy of the chant and type it
into here ...

The other memorable thing was seeing the reactions people had when
offered mead for breakfast on sunday morning.  (See, there was this
feast and we -- Phillip the Pilgrim and myself -- made 5 gallons
of St Faustus' quick mead for the feast.  But for some reason, even
