From: MALICE@ISIS.MIT.EDU
Subject: killing blows

It occurs to me that the folk of the SCA are opperating under the handicap of 
what used to be an amusing fantacy and is now a missaprehension that we can no 
longer afford.  I refer to the concept of the "killing" blow.

A fighter is supposed to ask him(her)self, "if i had been wearing such and 
such a type of armor and had the sword that hit me posessed an edge, would it 
have killed me?" and if the answer is "yes" then the fighter "dies", crumpling 
to the ground and twiching or executing a neat back flip.

Now, I will admit that in a war a certain amount of killing goes on, 
especially among the foot soldiers, and that in period tourneys a certain 
number of deaths and permenant disablements were expected, especially in the 
melees, HOWEVER...

It is simply not plausible that in a tourney only the victor would have 
survived, or that every encounter between armed men was entered with the 
combatants thinking "one of us will not come out of this alive."  There are 
period descriptions of tourneys.  They were sporting events, all the ladies 
came to watch and cheer granting ribbons and sleeves and whatnot to those 
fighters whom they favored and afterward tables were spread with wonderfull 
banquets under the tents on the grass.  Sometimes people died.  more often 
they did not.  Think about it.  A fighter on the tourney circuit who 
invariably killed his opponants would soon find few who wished to meet him on 
the field of honor and many whos friends had died by his hand who would be 
glad to teach him moderation.  Also a fighter who is defeated and who must 
ransom his armour etc back from the victor may be good for a few more gold 
peices later, while a dead one isnt good for much at all.  In wars as well the 
richer knights were seised for ransom rather than killed whenever possible.

Church and state were united in their dissaproval of acctivities that 
diminished thier tax base and their supply of fighters in their defence.  
Dueling was frequently illegal (although even duels were not invariably 
fatal--one might fight only to first blood, and when pistols came in one didnt 
fire at ones opponant until one or the other dropped, on had only one shot, 
and deloping-firing into the air-was an opption).  Crusades were strongly 
encouraged and very popular, not only because of the booty obtainable, but 
because one could kill one's opponants (and also civilians, women, children, 
small dogs, and sheep) with the blessing of the church.

Enough.  I conclude that the question fighters should be asking themselves is, 
"if I were wearing such & such armor and had the blade that hit me had had an 
edge, would it have dissuaded me from wishing to fight further?"  A fighter 
who consistantly "kills" his opponant is hitting too hard, and the church, the 
state, his lady, and his fellow fighters should tell him so.

