Greetings all!

Anyone who delights as I do in the interesting paths taken by language
over the years, will find great pleasure in the book "An Exaltation of
Larks".  This books is a compilation and discussion of period and
modern collective nouns, more often called "terms of venery" or
"venereal nouns", since they originally were invented for the beasts
of the hunt.  

In the 15th century, it appears to have been a courtly game to invent
and collect these terms, which were applied not only to animals and
birds, but also to people in various occupations.  They appear in
collections in many period books, notably those manuals on courtly
behavior exemplified by the Boke of St. Agnes.  A selection of such
words, as translated in "An Exaltation of Larks",

A sounder of boars
A skulking of foxes
A shrewdness of apes
A neverprosper of jugglers
A blarney of tapsters

I can list more if people are enjoying this...

The game is played in the SCa as well.  The debate over the proper
term for a crowd of heralds has gone on for years, and has produced:

A pun of heralds
A cry of heralds
A field of heralds
A semy of heralds
A shout of heralds
A court of heralds
A display of heralds
An achievement of heralds
...and so on.




