I am forwarding this for a friend (Orilee J Ireland-Delfs) who can not send mail
to the ArpaNet.



--------------------------------------------------------------------
First, let me introduce myself.  I am Lady Orianna vander Delft of Winfield.  I
live on the eastern fringes of the Barony of Thescorre (Rochester, NY) and have
been active in the SCA for about 8 years.

After reading the comments about "swordjocks" vs. well-rounded fighters, I
thought I would tell you about an event that my husband (Lord Friedrich
Tomasson) and I have autocratted for two years in a row now and will be holding
again next year.

We borrowed the idea from the Kingdom of An Tir (it's amazing what ideas you can
get from reading other Kingdom newsletters).  The event is called Sergeant's and
Yeoman's and the idea is to run a competition that involves seven areas of
expertise.

The areas are: martial arts, strategy & tactics, heraldry, gaming, dance,
performance, and courtesy.  Next year we are adding calligraphy.  Each
contestant selects one area of the martial arts to compete in, either rattan,
fencing, or archery (we added fencing since Thescorre has a large fencing
group).  Besides competing in a martial tournament, the contestants must take a
written test in strategy and tactics (SCA and historical references) and a
written test in heraldry (SCA - do you know what your kingdom arms look like?),
compete in a gaming tournament, perform three common dances before a group of
judges, perform a piece of some type (we accept "No S**t there we were" as well
as songs, stories, dance, etc.) for a group of judges, and be judged on courtesy
throughout the day.  Final scores in all areas are added up and the one with the
best score (depending upon your scoring system, we rank by 1st, 2nd, 3rd, etc.)
wins a belt.  We give three belts, one for rattan, one for fencing, and one for
archery.  At our first S&Y, the lady who won the Fencing belt came in dead last
in the fencing tournament.

Everyone enjoys participating.  We also run regular tournaments in rattan,
fencing, archery, and gaming (with Godiva Chocolates as prizes) for those who
wish to compete but not toward a belt.

Next year we plan on adding the calligraphy to the competition.  Each competitor
has to submit a letter of intent calligraphed in their own hand to the Baroness
of Thescorre.  We recieved some beautiful pieces of work this year and hope to
see more next year.

Just thought you all would be interested!

Orianna




