Gary,

Music is alive and well in the SCA. I am in San Antonio and
have been involved in things liking directing and singing in
madrigal choirs, playing in a recorder consort, and playing
for things fron court to dancing. Here in Ansteorra (Texas/Ok.)
we even have a College of Bards which is a group organising
and supporting bardic/minstrel performance. Basically, like
anything in the SCA, if something was done in the time
period of concern (Middle ages, pre-1600, whatever) there
is probably someone recreating it or interested in it. 

Different places will have different ideas about music and
performance. Here in Bjornsborg we have many Viking personas
and campfires often have people getting up to tell stories and recite
sagas. As befits the image, these can get very bawdy/humorous
very quickly. Other places may consider this poor taste..who's
to say. Know that even in this environment my nadrigal groups
went over extremely well.

As an aside you never *have* to do anything in the SCA (such
as learn to play the Lyre). However, I have never run across
someone playing one and it may prove to be something uniquely yours.

Filk songs (which I saw mentioned somewhere else) are recognizable
songs with different words set to them. One of the more
glaring examples might be "Silent Knight, Unconcious Knight" 
sung to the tune of the Christmas carol. The concept of filk
songs itself is a period idea but this can be an area of
controversy. (No flames please, I am not for or against them
just stating the facts 'mam.) I might sing the preceding Filk
at 2:00am when everyone has gotten stupid, but I wouldn'y sing
it at court. But that is just my personal call in this area.

Basically with a little common sense (how would *you* react to
bagpipes at 7:00 in the morning?) almost any form of
entertainment would usually be greatly appreciated. Good Luck!!

