Date: 10 Jun 88 21:49:30 GMT
From: haste+@andrew.cmu.edu  (Dani Zweig)
Subject: Set and Turn Single?
Message-Id: <UWg5Zey00UwBF2M0U-@andrew.cmu.edu>

How do you set and turn single?

It's not that we don't know how; we know too well.  We have over half a dozen
methods in use -- typically simultaneously, within the same dance!

Our 'generic' STS is a single to the left followed by a single to the right for
the man, while the lady takes a single to the right followed by a single to the
left.  Man's right hand is holding lady's left hand.  They then both turn in
place (so that the joined hands initially move towards the man's left).
Variations:  Sometimes the singles get changed to triples:  left-right-left,
right-left-right.  Sometimes the single, instead of left-together becomes
step-onto-left-kick-right-foot-leftward.  Sometimes this is all done without
holding hands.  Sometimes the turn single becomes a walk around a small circle.
 All of these may be done with small precise steps, with leaps, or with
anything in between.

More variations:  While the man does single-left/single-right, the lady does
likewise, thus moving in the opposite directions.  Or they start with
single-right.  Or the steps, instead of to the side, are at forty-five degree
angles forward, so the dancers are moving towards each other.

I'm *not* trying for an exhaustive list of all ways set-and-turn-single can be
done.  I'm cataloguing ways I've *seen* it done.  And when half a dozen of
these are all being used by various dancers in the same dance, that dance
becomes a bit painful to watch.

QUESTIONS:  How do you standardize?  *Do* you standardize?  Does anybody have
documentary evidence favoring some of these steps over others?  Advice?

advTHANKSance

--Dani of the Seven Wells

