Date: Thu, 9 Jun 88 11:06:44 EDT
From: justin@inmet.inmet.com (Mark Waks)
Message-Id: <8806091506.AA22033@inmet.inmet.com>
Subject: Bureaucracy & scouting

[Another re-post.]

Greetings to all from Justin du Coeur. The following is a bit of a tirade,
about the current state of one aspect of SCA bureaucracy. Those gentles who
do not want their blood pressure raised a hair should probably skip onto the
next message; I'm in a *very* sarcastic mood, and am likely to be a bit rude.

I look at the SCA's bureaucracy with growing horror. I know that it's not a 
new problem; I have issues of the baronial newsletter dating back 12-15 years
that were already complaining about the bureaucracy. But I think that things 
are getting rather extreme.

Now, I recognize that a certain amount of bureaucracy is necessary; the mundane
world *loves* to heap rules upon rules. A certain amount of bureaucracy is
even beneficial; I think that Arval's comment about keeping awards somewhat
consistent across geographic boundries is a good point. However, there seems
to be an increasing tendency towards unnecessary (and to my eyes harmful)
bureaucracy. The particular topic of the day is scouting in the East Kingdom.

When I went to my first Pennsic, four years ago, I discovered the pastime of
scouting. It suited my skills ideally; I'm not strong, but I'm pretty fast
and reasonably forest-wise. I was hooked up with Branswatch, the East's
guerilla fighting outfit, where you had to be fast just to keep up with the
armored fighters (much less keep ahead of them). I would scout with Branswatch
until they split up/got killed, then generally go freelance, keeping the
Eastern armies appraised of each others' movements. I broke a lot of the
"normal" rules of scouting, but did quite well in that war, and the two
following it.

About a year and a half ago, an official EK scouts office came into being.
This office had the task of "organizing" the scouts. I didn't care for this
idea much, but didn't have much idea of how to object to it publically.
Since I wasn't at Pennsic last year, I didn't realize just *how*
organized this office was trying to be. More recently, I've been hearing
rumors that one has to pre-authorize to become a scout, that one *must*
hook up with a unit, and such things. This disturbed me greatly, but I
simply decided that I wouldn't scout if I couldn't deal with the red tape
involved.

The last straw came last night. I received a rather belated letter from the
scout's office, which I will quote parts from.

The intro: Unto Mark Wales (sic) ...

The gist of the first sheet is that one *must* not only be trained, but
must be authorized as a scout before one will be allowed into the woods
battle at Pennsic. And that training is not only that one must be provably
safe in the woods, but must be trained to do everything *correctly*. Even
fighters don't have to go through this!

The real kicker is the bottom of the first sheet, though. After spending
several sentences telling me how I must contact one of my Local Marshalls
to be trained, and that ONLY (emphasis theirs) the signature of one of the
Local Marshalls will be accepted on my Qualification card, I go to the name
of the first of the listed Local Marshalls, which is:

		Justan (sic) de (sic) Cour (sic)
		c/o Mark Whatts (sic)

So, it appears that *I* am one of the only two people qualified to say
that I am qualified. Great. It appears to me that this bureaucracy is not
only a bad idea, but the one hand doesn't even know what the other is
saying. A badly run bureaucracy is the *only* thing worse than a good
bureaucracy, to my mind.

Then I get to the second sheet. According to this, the last Curia ordained
that, to be a scout, I must send *proof* of membership and age. They
suggest sending photocopies of my Driver's Licence and SCA membership 
card. And, just to make it complete, they list at the bottom the 
information they have on me, wherein *every* important field (SCA name,
Mundane name, address, and phone number) is not only out of date, but
downright *wrong*.

What has happened to scouting? Four years ago, this was what you did if
you wanted to get some exercise in the forest battle, but weren't an
authorized fighter. Now, you *aren't* allowed to participate if you're
under 18 (BOD ruling), you must go through a course of training, and
you must be an SCA member to participate. Even fighters don't have to
go through this! F**k it. Pardon my French, but this bureaucracy has
managed to completely eliminate any traces of *fun* from scouting. It's
no longer something that you do at the War to enjoy yourself; now, it's
work. I fully expect them to introduce awards for scouting within two
years; the award-driven mentality is, in my experience, closely tied to
the bureaucratic one (after all, if it isn't fun anymore, you have to have
some reason to do it). Sorry, I shan't be scouting at Pennsic anymore.

This is one of the major problems I'm having with the Society today. It
isn't bureaucracy per se that I object to, but unnecessary bureaucracy.
I could understand all of the rigamarole about making sure that scouts
were properly trained (well, not *all* of it, but at least some) if we
were still allowing 12-year-olds into the woods. But we aren't; you have
to be an adult to go in! I can understand *encouraging* people to get
some amount of training, so that they will be more effective as scouts,
but *requiring* it? And what possible justification is there for 
requiring proof of membership? Are we really at the point where gentles
who aren't members are considered to be un-people?

It seems to me that things are worsening, gradually. I ask everyone who is
in a position of power: *think* before you make a rule. Is this rule
necessary? Is it worth the small bit of additional stratification it adds
to the SCA? Remember, it isn't the big rules that are the problem, but the
small ones. When BOD makes a grandly stupid decision (which they do about
once every two years), *everyone* in the Known World tells them so. If your
new rule is stupid, it's not so likely that it will be noticed until it
has been locked into India Ink iron. Remember: a guideline is almost
*always* better than a rule, and common sense is usually better than a
guideline.

Please, everyone, work on this problem. Otherwise, within five years or
so, I'm going to find myself in a position of having to join (or found)
a splinter group, just so that I can have some *fun*. And that would be
very, very sad.

In service to the Society (but dreading the day that he has to start filling
out paperwork in order to *dance*),

