Message-Id: <8806092236.AA03257@godot.psc.edu>
Subject: RE: Bureaucracy and Scouting
Date: Thu, 09 Jun 88 18:36:57 -0400
From: wadlow@godot.psc.edu

*sigh*

Yes, the fate of scouting does seem to have fallen into the 
hands of the bureaucrats.  I was very shocked to find out 2 weeks
before pennsic that I had to authorize as a scout in order to
participate in the woods battle.  This was one little piece of 
red-tape I was able to cut through, although it wasn't pretty.

It seems as though it is currently more difficult to be a scout than
it is to be a fighter.  Hell... as I understand it, you don't
necessarily have to be a member to be an authorized fighter, and
fighting has considerably more potential for harm than scouting.  Why
then, is it harder to be a scout?  

  The other major problem that has been recurring for the past few
years is the matter of protection and such.  Half the of BMDL's scout
helms were made *AT* Pennsic with close supervision of the marshalls
just so we could get helms that passed.  We were trying hard to avoid
getting screwed the way we did a year before when most of our scouts
were told ~30 minutes before the battle started that their helms
weren't up to spec, and they couldn't enter the woods.  It seems that
there is no official guidelines as to what a helm should and should
not be, but everyone has there own idea as to what should be allowed.
The open faced helm that was perfectly legal two years ago has now
been deemed unsafe.

I wasn't too thrilled with the helm I wore last year at war.  It
served very well at blocking vision and restricting hearing, and all
and all, cutting down my efficiency as a scout.  The saving grace was
that it wasn't what seemed to be the standard midrealm scouting helm
which looks far too similar to a fighters helm for me to be
comfortable with.  Frankly, I have no desire to have a fighter mistake
me for an enemy fighter, and take a few swings at me.  (I generally
don't let them get that close) The open faced helms that *USED* to be
legal seemed to serve their purpose well, and I'd really like to see
them return.


I am in favor of giving new scouts some basics on not getting hurt.
It would also be a win to teach people what poison ivy looked like,
and that chivalry isn't just for fighters anymore. One thing that I
have stressed to the new scouts that I recruit is that you are there
at Pennsic to have fun.  If what you are doing isn't fun, then
reconsider why you are doing it.  People seem to be making it more and
more difficult to keep scouting fun.  If it doesn't look like it will
be fun, I probably won't do it.

enough ramblings for the moment...

				Ruaidhri O'Foirbhithe
				BMDL Scout


