Date: 7 Jun 88 16:08:47 GMT
From: aramis.rutgers.edu!paul.rutgers.edu!styx.rutgers.edu!joshua@rutgers.edu  (Joshua Mittleman)
Subject: Re: Japanese Personas
Message-Id: <Jun.7.12.08.45.1988.29131@styx.rutgers.edu>

Greetings!

First of all, you would probably be interested in knowing that a few
years back, TI published an issue concentrating on Japan and Japanese
persona.   I'm not sure which issue it was (Siobhan?), but it was very
well done.  

Japan had its own rather sophisticated system of heraldry.  Japanese
devices are called "mon".  Mon developed along very similar lines to
Western European arms.  The insignia were hereditary, and were originally
used for identification on the field of battle.  Of course, they used
different kinds of designs, but they are philosophically very similar.
Originally (12th century, I think), mon were very simple, generally
consisting of single charges, and were almost exclusively used as
military insignia.  As Japanese medieval culture developed, mon became
closely tied to feudal rank and to political stature.  Most mon are
radially symettric, and use floral patterns. Many appear within a
circular frame.  However, there are many different types of designs
which were used, and styles varied over time.  A good source for mon
design is "Japanese Design Motifs", available at many large book
stores.  If you are interested, let me know & I'll give you the publisher
and so on.  A second important point about  mon design is that colors
were not specified.  Mon were designed with dark charges on a light
background, or light charges on a dark background.  The actual colors
used depended on the circumstances.  For example, if you have a
dark-on-light mon, and you are making a pale red kimono, you would
stamp the mon in a darker red.

The SCA College of Arms recognizes that mon are a legitimate form of
heraldry, and encourages those with Japanese persona to register
properly designed mon.  In keeping with period practice, we only
register mon in black and white.  Mon must meet the same standards of
difference as European-style armory, and must be clearly blazonable in
standard terms.  Of course, they may (and should) use Japanese design
elements.   

A note on Japanese names: the construction of Japanese names is a
tricky thing, and one which I do not fully understand.  In the SCA,
Japanese names are expected to be of the form <family name> <personal
name>, without any honorific elements.  The best way to choose each
name is from history books, lists of period names, and the like.  If
you need some specific sources, I will be glad to suggest some.  There
is a Japanese expert in the College of Arms, Monsho Herald.  If you
would like to contact him, I will send you his address.
