     About a year ago the same thing bugged me until I thought about it a
little more closely. We were experiencing the usual misconceptions about
fealty and what an oath of fealty ment. Master Gerhard Von Nordflammen had
already written the first "In Defense of Feudalism" article, I was moved to
embellish upon it. This originally appeared in an issue of the MARK, the 
Barony of Westermark's newsletter and I hope it in part answers Lord Harald's 
question about what the Dream is.

Editorial - IN DEFENSE OF FEUDALISM - Part II
-----------------------------------------------

     I live in the twentieth century, a technological wonderworld where a 
man can travel faster than the speed of sound, escape the gravity of earth,
travel to other worlds. A place where I can use machines to cook, create
entertainment, adjust my environment, even think for me. A world which one
hundred years ago was as fictional as any you or I could read about in any
one of a hundred 'recreational' publications today.

     Yet I choose of my own free will to belong to a Society which harkens us 
back to the days of yore, when armour clad knights rode in defense of their
Lord's lands, where a man's word was more binding than any lawyer's 
contractual agreement, where ballads were sung about heroic deeds more awe 
inspiring than an evening of 'Miami Vice' or 'Dallas' on the one eyed monster.

     Perhaps the strangest part of all this is I'm not alone. This is a world
wide fraternity with thousands of members. We share a collective "Dream", a 
dream of the Middle Ages as we would like to see it. Sure it has some elements
of fantasy involved, the Middle Ages was a horrible place to live. But there's
something about the idea of stepping out of this century and into another one 
which appeals to us. It appeals to us so much that we've developed some pretty
sophisticated rules and regulations to insure we stay within some sort of 
boundary, a framework if you will, so that the illusion of the Middle Ages 
remains as much as possible. We understand this and are willing to work within
those guidelines so that the illusion is maintained for all of us.

    But what happens when these guidelines, these rules, disturb the illusion?

    For the most part, the rules and regulations within the Society are mostly
good, common sense rules. They are the kinds of things which help us maintain 
a level of safety, promote good relations with our neighbors, help maintain 
the illusion of the Middle Ages. Since not everyone's "Dream" is the same, 
they bind those of us together who would fragment due to minor differences of
aesthetics. Every time we get a new King, we get some new rules, every time 
the Board of Directors meets, we get a few new rules, and so on until those 
areas which were potential hazard areas are fine tuned for the benefit of all.

    No society which imposes regulations upon it's members is perfect. Usually
there is a small minority who opposes some facet of the organization because
he/she feels that it doesn't meet with their approval. Sometimes the rules 
themselves are just plain bad rules. They favor a faction or support a 
minority viewpoint to the deteriment of all. Sometimes they become political 
footballs, pushed across the field in some ritualistic contest of wills to 
prove the superior point of view. When this happens it's to the sorrow of the 
society which supports such activities. Laws or rules which trample over the 
bodies of people to support favoritism or breed elitism for whatever reason in
whatever form, should be discouraged. 

     In medieval times, the King's word was law. From the Crown the law spread
downward through the social register, each level of nobility bearing a 
responsibility to the level above and below it. Even the Crown was not exempt,
for if the peasants became to discontent they could always rise up in revolt
and overthrow their oppressors. The ruling class had to balance their 
interests and the peasants needs carefully, lest they find themselves locked 
in their own dungeons or impailed upon their own gatespikes.

     In the Society the King's word is law. From the Crown comes the changes 
in the law, which hopefully enrich the Society and help strengthen and 
maintain the illusion. During the Coronation procedure the King and his Queen 
swear to the populous of the Kingdom that they will defend and support the 
Kingdom until such times as they depart from their thrones, death take them, 
or the world end. The Nobles and Great Officers of the land come forward and 
swear fealty to the Crown, the Crown swears fealty to them, and so on down the
line. Thus is the reciprocal nature of the Society fealty, King to noble, 
noble to vassal, just as it was eons ago. Thus a part of the Dream we believe 
in, lives.

     Most of us will never kneel before the Crown to swear fealty, we instead 
look to the rest of the Nobility and Chivalry, we swear to the Knight or 
Baron, (or in the certain cases Prince or Princess, or Crown appointed 
authority) in order to fulfill our obligation. Just as in medieval times, 
nobility takes on an important role, from the lowliest Knight to the Great 
Dukes of the Realm. For in swearing fealty to them, we swear fealty to the 
Crown itself. When they then kneel before the Crown it's as if we knelt before
the Crown, we have "pledged by proxy" our support and our loyalty. Such is the
nature of the beast.

     But there exists a problem in the Society which the real medievalists had
a solution for. What do you do when a ruler abuses the power granted? In the
Society we have no way to "rise in revolt" if the ruler abuses the authority 
and trust we have placed in him. Further, if we disapprove of the Crown's 
action and are so bold as to speak out, we are reminded that the "King's word 
is law," which is tantamount to insisting that we remain silent lest we be 
found "guilty" of breaking the oath of fealty which we swore to the Crown.

     Yet, didn't the King swear the same oath to us?

     In most matters, the King, whoever he may be, usually makes good, sound 
decisions which help rather than hinder the development of the Society. Yet
we have also seen our share of "bad" decisions, those laws, edicts, and
appointments to offices or stations which have caused major factional splits, 
those which have fragmented the solidarity of the Dream, those which have 
caused dissension in the ranks. Fealty is important to all stations in a 
medieval environment, and no matter who the King of our Society is, it is
best for all concerned that the King remembers that he is responsible to the 
people in the same way the people are responsible to the Crown. The duty of 
the King therefore, as the flame of fealty illuminates it, becomes crystal 
clear. He is the Defender of the Dream first, Defender of the Land second, 
defender of special interests.....never! He must strive to work for the good 
of the Kingdom and the people in it or else he fails in his oath to his 
subjects, in his oath to the Crown.

     The Crown of any Kingdom is the symbol of the trust which the subjects
of the Kingdom place in the King who wears it. It is the emblem which squarely
rests the authority and responsibility of the Kingdom and it's subjects
directly upon one person's shoulders. It is also the symbol of love that the 
people have in their Kingdom, in their Society, in their King. It is why it's 
weight is so great, for it bears the load of the decisions made under it, now 
and forever more. Kings may come and go but the Crown is forever.

     I do not envy the rulers who wear those Crowns, for theirs is a world 
filled with decisions which must be tempered by their judgement and wisdom so
that the Dream lives on in all. I sympathize with their plight, balancing the 
needs and desires of their subjects so that all will be pleased with their 
decisions. Therefore I support them when I can and when I am able. Part of 
that support is to gently remind them of their obligations to their subjects 
when I perceive that those obligations overlooked. I would be remiss in my 
oath to my Kingdom if I didn't.

     Though the responsibility of the Kingdom lies on their shoulders, though 
the ultimate decisions for the welfare of the Kingdom must rest with them, it
is these decisions which add or subtract to the collective might of the Dream 
as perceived by their subjects. They either add to it's strength, creating a 
solid illusion which everyone believes or tear away at it bit by bit until the
mundane framework begins to show through. We as the Crown's subjects must do 
play our parts as well, including the offering of council or constructive 
criticism when needed. This doesn't mean that the Crown should change it's
opinions or decisions to meet with our criteria,(for who is to say that one
version of the Dream has any more validity than any other?), but to simply 
listen to the opinions provided, from whatever quarter they might arise.

     The Society for Creative Anachronism should be large enough to encompass 
everyone's dreams about what the Middle Ages should be like, both fantastic
and realistic. In the areas where overlap is involved, the Crown should weigh 
all factors involved, take all council offered. It is the responsibility that 
the Crown undertook when they swore their oath. It is the foundation of 
feudalism. It is the Dream of which we speak, a blending of everyone's idea
of the SCA.

     If I didn't love my Kingdom I would remain silent. But my oath of fealty 
causes me to speak thusly. For by swearing fealty through my Knight and my 
Baron I too have taken an obligation to defend my Kingdom, to help support the
collective illusion known as the Dream. To do less would be to break this 
oath, an oath I have with myself, my peers, and my King.

In Service to the West Kingdom,

Lord Arron Renyard

(This editorial is the sole opinion of the author. It does not express an 
 official view of anyone in the Barony of Westermark, the Kingdom of the West,
 or the Society of Creative Anachronism.)

