   A number of comments about knighthoods for unassociated
   fighters:  but first a disclaimer:  
   
      I do not wish to insult anyone's intelligence.  What I have
      to say may seem obvious.  It is.  I just feel that we may
      be overlooking some of these points _because of_ their
      obviousness.
       
      
    1) Of course belts are generally given to squires:  we expect
       this, in general.  The reasons are, again, obvious:
       fighting households choose members, and knights choose
       squires, largely on the basis of their interest in
       fighting: i.e. the likelihood that they will stick
       with it long enough to acquire some skill.  They also
       tend to give a lot of "extra" encouragement and assistance
       to their novices.  That is exactly the point of being
       a squire in the first place.
       
    2) Some abuse of the rights of non-squired novices has
       been described.  My personal impression is that although
       I'm sure it is the case, it also seems to be a rare
       exception to the rule of general well-meaning
       encouragement to all.  
       
       My experience is that there is less "personal" politics
       among fighters than exists in the rest of the Society.
       Yes, this is probably because fighters take the the SCA a
       little less seriously; perhaps that is exactly the point.
       Regardless, I consider it a mark in favor of fighters (and
       "even" stick jocks). 
                           
  
  Final disclaimer:  Views expressed herein are my own and not to
              the best of my knowledge shared with anyone at all. 
 
 
 
