In article <8805271542.AA06062@tut.cis.ohio-state.edu> EDDIE@ISIS.MIT.EDU writes:
>jf period small tactics and small group combats.  I would be interested in 
>seeing some documentation on fighting styles for one-on-one combats in the 
>medieval period, because I've never seen it.   I would be much more in favor 
>
There are a few sources; most of them are in either the Folger or the
Huntingdon Libraries.  The Book of the Sword (newer edition) has a list of
"period sources" but misses some major ones, for example a 15th century
manuscript that was used for backgrounds in catalog for the Tower of London
Exhibit here in the U.S.  Late 16th century tournaments are documented
in the woodcuts that decorate one of the late Elizabethan books on 
the code of honor (they show two people in three-quarter harnesses with
burgonets and two weapoons, one a long armor-smasher and the second a
shorter parrying dagger (still 2 feet or so long.)

>I also seem to remember that one of the reasons the rapier was invented was to 
>deal with nuts in plate armor.  And that in any given area of Europe, plate 
>armor was only in style for less than a hundred years, as only a massed unit 
>of cavalry in heavy armor was good against rabble armies with pitchforks, and 
>a lone "knight" would be pulled down and off in a matter of minutes.  
>
The estoc was the arming sword of the earlier period, and it was basically a
long metal punch.  The Italians like war hammers, which were basically also
sheet metal punches on one side and hammers on the other.  The halberd was
useful as a can opener; local experiments with the Middle Kingdom's halberds
(conducted by the makers) showed that even light blows would split heavy sheet
metal.  Armor was basically ended by the gun, not the rapier; descriptions of
16th century tournaments (including some on foot) suggest that good armor
was not easy to punch.  There is a so-so book called "Old Sword Days and
Old Sword Ways" that has a little information on this, but with no sources.

