Date: Fri, 3 Jun 88 02:16 EST
From: JOEL WELLING <WELLING@CPWSCA.PSC.EDU>
Subject: on restructuring the Registrar's office

I recently had a bit of a discussion about the Registrar's Office with a
well-informed source.  I think there is a general perception that the office
is not being well handled, even among the powers that be, but since there
exists (as far as I know) no written statement about what the office *does*
it is hard to judge.  So please understand that the suggestions I am about
to make may be founded on inadequate information.  If anyone out there can
send me a formal statement of the duties of the Registrar's office, please
do so!

One problem with the office is that membership records are kept using a
home-brewed and apparently suboptimal piece of Cobol code.  For example,
one restriction of the code is that it cannot produce lists of memberships
that must invariably expire.  If a person has not submitted a check by a
certain day in a given month, there is no question that that person's
membership will expire and not be renewed at the end of the month.  If a
list of such people could be generated, it could have (for example) prevented
the bit of unhappiness with Lucan's brief tenure as Prince of the East.
As a programmer it seems pretty trivial to me to extract such a list, but
it is (as I understand it) beyond the capabilities of the current code.

The obvious solution to this is to replace the code with any of a number
of off-the shelf databases.  There are some hindrances to this, however.
The computer on which this stuff runs is neither terribly new nor terribly
popular, so it would probably have to be replaced at a cost of perhaps
$5000.  Also I get the impression that the project has not met with resounding
support from the Registrar, whose husband wrote and maintains the current
code.

Another problem is that membership is currently inexorably linked to getting
a newsletter.  A person is by definition a member the first month their
newsletter arrives.  This introduces delays which are, in my opinion,
unnecessary.  A more natural solution would be for the Registrar to immediately
note the membership of a new member, and then forward his or her newsletter
requests to the appropriate chronicler(s) for processing.  Let the chroniclers
maintain their own subscription lists;  that way non-members can subscribe
to newsletters too.  I believe this is the way the publications of other
organizations I belong to (admittedly larger than the SCA) are handled.

I agree that the Registrar's office could be decentralized.  I don't think
the idea of having local exchequers process membership forms is desirable.
They are a scurvey bunch;  I've been one for a number of years so I know.
However, it seems simple enough to me to create a Kingdom office to handle
new memberships.  That officer could enter the new names and other data
into a computer of his or her own, print up the membership cards and mail
them out, and (say monthly) download the new names to the corporate office.
If we assume 1900 payed members in the Kingdom (true of the East, the largest
kingdom), that comes out to about 37 renewals per week.  This seems pretty
manageable.  

Of course, I can't comment on the Registrar's other duties because I don't
know what they are, but I suspect that memberships are a large part of the
job and the whole office would run more smoothly if they were straightened
out.

Magnus de Cnoc an Iora
Debatable Lands, East Kingdom
(mka Joel Welling)

