From:	DECWRL::"salley@canisius.CSNet" "David Salley  31-May-88 1409 EDT"  2-JUN-1988 18:18
To:	SCA-REQUEST%mc.lcs.mit.edu@RELAY.CS.NET
Subj:	

Gentles, with all of the discussion currently on the net about "Cabbages and
Kings", I thought I'd post an article I recently wrote for AESTEL, the newletter
for the Western Region of the East Kingdom.  Feel free to comment.
 
 
		       AN ALTERNATIVE TO CROWN TOURNAMENTS
		  by Lord Dagonell Collingwood of Emerald Lake
 
Every once in a while at a post-rev, I hear somebody say that the SCA puts
too much emphasis on sword-fighting and not enough on the other things that
we do.  This usually leads into a discussion of Crown and Coronet Tourneys and 
other possible methods of choosing a ruler.
 
I'd like to offer one possible method that I worked out strictly as an
intellectual excercise.  I am NOT starting a campaign to change the way we
elect our sovreigns for either the kingdom or the incipient principality.  
I offer it only as a topic for discussion.
 
There are basically four categories of activities in the SCA; sword-fighting,
archery, fencing and a catch-all called arts and sciences.  I am not putting
down arts and sciences, my lady and I are co-MOAS for our barony.  I am simply
stating that A&S covers a wide variety of activities.
 
There are also three levels of activities; barony, region and kingdom.  I
realize that other levels exist i.e. canton, shire, province, dominion,
principality, etc. but my example only concerns itself with the three listed.
It could easily be expanded to include these others as separate or equivalent
levels.
 
Anyone who wins *any* competition at a barony level event receives one point.
Be it a fighting tourney, archery shoot or baronial bard contest, s/he gets
one point.  Winning first place at a regional level event is worth three
points.  Second place is worth one.  At a kingdom event, winning a 
competition earns five points; second place, three; and third place, one.
After six months, whomever has the highest point total is the new prince.
 
Advantages :
1.) You can eliminate any residency requirement because the competition
itself takes six months of *active* involvement.
 
2.) You can eliminate any previously-attended event requirement because
anyone who only attends a few events a year isn't going to win.
 
3.) The system favors the Renaissance type of individual.  A person who
does moderately well in several areas is more likely to win than someone
who is superior is just one field.  We would be very likely to get a ruler
who has at least a working knowledge of a number of areas of the SCA rather
than just expertise in fighting.
 
4.) It lessens the temptation to "rhino-hide".  The final round of a Crown
Tourney is winner-take-all.  The temptation to call a just-barely-acceptable
blow as "light" is enormous.  Under this new system, the difference between
first and second place in a tourney is only two points towards a cumulative
total.
 
5.) The bias against women is eliminated.  I know women are allowed to
enter Crown but they are at a physical disadvantage.  
 
	"Men have an average of 17 percent more muscle mass than women."1 
 
	"Female physiology dictates that the average woman is simply not 
	as fast on her feet as the average man. Witness the winners of 
	marathons.  Though the gap between men's and women's times has 
	been decreasing over the years, men still consistantly beat women.  
	The reasons for this are not mysterious.
 
	Women possess a large pelvis which is required in the process of
	reproduction, consequently, their strides are shorter and less 
	efficient than men's.  In addition, muscles and the brain rely on 
 	oxygen to perform at peak levels.  Because men generally have larger 
	hearts, their hearts pump more oxygen carrying hemoglobin per beat 
	than do women's hearts.  Obviously, the more oxygen the muscles and 
	brain receive, the more energy they can produce."2
 
6.) The system has been tried and proven workable.  The U. S. Chess Federation
runs a year long competition each year on a similiar system.3  The American
Junior Golf Association and Golf magazine select each year's Junior All
American Golf Team this way as well.4
 
Disadvantages :
1.) It would require changing the current laws regarding Crown and Coronet
Tourneys to adopt this system.
 
2.) It would mean more paperwork but not as much as would seem at first glance.
All of the activities listed, sword-fighting, archery, fencing and arts &
sciences, have baronial level officers who report to kingdom superiors.  In
the worst case, you'd have to create a minor Kingdom officer whose job it
would be to co-ordinate the reports and keep track of everyone's score.
 
3.) We've been using the old system for over twenty years.  People would be
mistrustful of a new system simply because it is a new system.  If the old
method has worked for twenty years, why bother to change it?  Changing the
system would require a huge amount of effort.  And some people would be
against it.
 
4.) There would be less suspence and anticipation.  The morning of Crown
Tourney, no one knows who's going to be the next King.  Under the point
system, it might be well known if someone has a commanding lead, which might
discourage other competitors.  One possible solution might be to keep the
point totals a secret until the winner is announced in court.  The archery
points at Pennsic are handled this way.  You get rumours and speculation,
but nobody is quite sure.  Another possibility would be to have the COUPLE
with the highest point total become the next King and Queen.
 
5.) The Ice Dragon Festival doesn't fit anywhere in this system.  The 
rattan fighting and the fencing would probably count as baronial competitions, 
but how do you rate the Arts and Sciences Pentathlon?  Technically its a 
baronial competition because it takes place at a baronial level event.  But the
scores are reported to the East Kingdom Arts and Sciences Office, so is it 
baronial or kingdom level?  One competition or two?  And then there's the 
structure of the Pent itself.  It's 1 pentathlon with 12 categories and 47 
sub-categories.  Do you count it as 1 competition? 12? 47?
 
Things That Stay the Same :
1.) Surprise!!  We still have a Crown Tournament.  Its one last chance to
win just a few more points before the new Crown Prince and Princess are 
announced at dinner that evening.  What's changed is that its not a do-or-die 
proposition anymore.  You can lose the tournament and still be declared 
the next Prince/ss.
 
2.) Letters of Intent are still required.  Someone may just like entering
( and winning! ) competitions and not be interested in the throne.  The other
rules about suitable consort, etc. would still apply as well.
 
Finally, I would like to remind everyone once again, that I developed this
system strictly as an intellectual excercise and I offer it only as a post-revel
discussion topic.  I am NOT interested in trying to change the system.  I 
welcome all correspondance and my mailing address is : Lord Dagonell Collingwood
of Emerald Lake, c/o David P. Salley, 136 Shepard Street, Buffalo, New York 
14212-2029.
 
