Greetings,

A gentle recently inquired as to a recipe for making mead.  I am
yet but an egg at this game of making mead, but do have a small
amount of knowledge in such matters.  It also happens that I am
a bit of a pack rat when it comes to knowledge and while rummaging
around the insides of my home computer found some postings which
I'd saved on the subject.

First the recipe which I've been using so far.  It's really pretty 
simple ... A quart of honey to a gallon of water.  Then add in
a little bit (1/4 tsp) of tannin and acids (3 tsp of malic acid,
and 1 1/2 tsp of tartaric acid).  Also some "energizer" which
is a yeast nutrient.  Finally you sterilize the mixture, which
means to either heat it to boil or near boil or to mix in some
chemicals which kills bacteria (campden tablet).  You let this 
sit a day then add the yeast to it, attach a fermentation lock,
and wait for the vigorous fermentation.  The last batch I started
started fermenting almost immediately...!

The recipe came from _Winemakers_Recipe_Handbook_ which was given
to me by the people at Semplex of U.S.A. (PO Box 11476, Minneapolis
MN 55411).  It works.  I've seen the same basic recipe in other
places including the Knowne World Handbook, a book which is sold
by Cariadoc, the _Making_Mead_ book which will be talked about
below, articles in TI, and so forth.

Anyway, the results of my pack-rat fetishes ...

