From: Dick Dunn <rcd@ico.isc.com>
Newsgroups: rec.food.drink
Subject: Mead, part 1 (information sources, background, terms)
Message-ID: <3243@ico.ISC.COM>
Date: 25 Mar 88 00:48:43 GMT
Organization: Interactive Systems Corp, Boulder, CO

Where to look for information on mead--these books are likely to be found
at your local beer/wine making supply shop; otherwise they can be ordered
from the American Homebrewers Association (AHA):

_Brewing_Mead_, Lt Col Robt Gayre and Charlie Papazian, 1986

_Making_Mead_, Bryan Acton and Peter Duncan, revised 1983

Gayre's section of the Gayre/Papazian book is most informative on the
history and traditions.  Gayre is somewhat of an authority; he was sought
out by the AHA for his expertise as they were trying to uncover knowledge
about meads.

If you want to know about making mead, FIND HOMEBREWERS!  There are lots of
homebrewing clubs--if you can't find one in your area, email a note back to
me and I'll find the info on the closest one.  There are mead categories
in AHA competitions.
- - - - -
What is mead?  It's a fermented beverage in which honey provides the sugars
for fermentation.  Some clarifications/corrections from other articles:

> The historical references aren't always clear...

and the matters have become somewhat worse because, as Gayre notes, mead
fell by the wayside some centuries ago as a cheaper (and not necessarily
better) substitute came along.

>...In one of my books, the author references
> a historical thing talking about a mead being served to some troops
> and the ingredients included Hops and ale yeast!  Yet usually Mead
> is thought of as a wine...
(and from another posting)
> Mead is honey beer, or honey wine. There is no real distinction between
> these two beverages except the amount of alcohol used,...

First, let's use narrow definitions of wine=fermented fruit (juice), beer=
fermented malt--then mead is neither.  If it doesn't have honey in it, it
isn't mead; if it has honey (as the main fermentable), it's either mead or
one of the variants (see below).  Alcoholic strength of mead is normally
stronger than beer; it may range from 10% alc vol up to wherever the yeast
give out (which is seldom over 15% vol).

Acton and Duncan explain the confusion mentioned:  The Anglo-Saxon word
"alu" (which sort of looks like "ale") really means mead; moreover, during
the Napoleonic wars, mead was made with a brewer's yeast, had hops added,
and was fermented to 4-6% alcohol--beer strength.  But it was still made
with honey.  Gayre also provides various historical bits.

> ...The weaker the mead, the sweeter it is...

No.  The normal procedures will either lead to (a) complete fermentation of
sugars or (b) as much fermentation as the yeast can handle, with some
residual sugar.  If you want a low-alcohol sweet mead, you have to take an
extra step to stop the yeast; this isn't as common so the sweet meads tend
to be the stronger ones.

Proper terms--although lots of homebrewers use "mead" for all sorts of
honey-based beverages (and not incorrectly so), the more precise terms are:
	mead = just fermented honey
	melomel = honey plus fruit juices
	pyment = honey plus grape juice (a "grape melomel")
	cyser = honey plus apple juice (an "apple melomel")
	metheglin = honey plus herbs
	hippocras = honey plus grape juice plus herbs (pyment flavored
		with herbs)
In the case of fruits, there is enough fruit or fruit juice added to make a
significant contribution to the alcohol.
