If you want recipes and techniques, look at the books suggested in my
previous article--
	_Making_Mead_ by Acton and Duncan, or _Brewing_Mead_ by Gayre and
	Papazian
There is a brief treatment of mead in:
	_The_Complete_Joy_of_Homebrewing_, by Charlie Papazian, 1984 (be
	sure you get the recent version, 300+ pages with a color cover)
and it's a good book on procedures anyway.

> I currently have a batch of "Barkshack Ginger Mead" aging in my "mead cellar".
> The recipe is from Charles Papazan's (sp?) book,...

Techniques for making mead have been evolving pretty rapidly in the past
few years.  Charlie's "Barkshack" recipe has been around for quite a while;
it's a very beer-like recipe which gives a lower-alcohol, sparkling, dry
mead (with some melomel variations possible).  Homebrewers have also
thought of the obvious: add honey to beer.  I've had some excellent amber
and dark beers with a couple of pounds of honey in a 5-gal batch.

>...You can make mead by following the beer recipe I posted recently,
> substituting honey for malt, and using champagne yeast...

Although Charlie's Barkshack has hops in it, it's probably a better idea to
start making meads without hops.  It will be easier to figure out what
you're doing and how it matures...there is an astringent character from the
honey which changes over time, and the taste is easier to follow without
hops in the way.  (If you make mead at a reasonable strength, you won't
need hops to preserve it.)

Also, you need either fruit/fruit juice or some source of acid added to a
mead--something you wouldn't do with a beer--plus yeast nutrients (see
below).  You don't boil a mead the way you do beer wort.

As I've said, a lot of the interest in mead comes from homebrewers, so
we've started working with beer-like procedures and recipes, working
outward as we've figured out what works.

But Charlie is well beyond what shows up in either _Complete_Joy_ or
_Brewing_Mead_ (and I sort of wish he'd write about his meads some more!)
He made a sweet still mead which was served slightly warmed at a winter
party a couple years ago; I still haven't forgotten how good it was!  He's
done still and sparkling, with and without fruit, sweet and dry, and he's
gotten good results for most of the combinations.  But one of the keys to
his success is that he just keeps on making meads, so that they have time
to age.  For most meads, drinking them too young is a waste.  (If it has a
taste like Listerine(R), it's probably too young!  That's the result of
immature honey flavors.)

A few recent changes in meads:
	- Boiling the honey is not favored as in the past.  This is said to
	  damage the flavor of the honey (and my experience confirms this).
	  It can be heated and held just below boiling long enough to
	  sterilize it--but you DO need to sterilize most honey that is of
	  interest for mead.
	- Hops aren't as common.  We're getting away from beer style, and
	  frankly, people aren't making the mistakes that produce off-
	  flavors which require something to hide them.

An interesting effect:  I've had several blueberry meads--all excellent,
and all retaining some sweetness even though the initial gravity is low
enough that they should have fermented out.  It would seem that there's
some non-fermentable sugar in blueberries that doesn't exist in most other
fruits.  (I don't like that explanation--seems pretty unlikely.)

A leftover question:
> P.S.  One thing that the book does not mention:  I am told that honey has a
>       natural fungicide in it (no added preservatives? :^)  that may cause
>       "stuck fermentation" if you do not add nutrients to help the yeastie
>       beasties get established.  You have to add the nutrients during the
>       boil, and get the yeast well started prior to pitching.  Anyone else
>       have experience with this?
Honey, in its natural state, tends to resist fungi and bacteria because of
the extremely high sugar concentrations.  It is also supposed to be
slightly bactericidal.  However, these properties are lost when the honey
is diluted to the strength appropriate to mead-making (which is why the
honey has to be sterilized).  The real problem is that honey is deficient
in certain nutrients needed by the yeast--they can grow for a while without
these nutrients, but not very well, and they won't complete the
fermentation properly.  You just use standard yeast nutrient; it should be
dissolved before adding to the mead, but need not be boiled.

Plain mead (without added fruit juices) is not sufficiently acidic, so it
also needs an addition there--some standard winemaking acid blend will
work.  (See the references for details.)

When using fruit or fruit juices (for melomels) you need to sterilize the
fruit but you should NOT boil it.  If you use whole fruit, boiling will
extract tannins from many fruits.  It will also extract and set pectin from
some fruits, enough that the mead will remain cloudy.
-- 
