From: wlinden@dasys1.uucp  (William Linden)
Subject: Royal style
Message-Id: <4717@dasys1.UUCP>

We seem to have lost a lot of alt.sca items during feed problems here, and I no
longer have the digest the original message appeared in. But this is in re-
ply to the person who classed "not wanting to be called Your Majesty" as a
solecism ranking with wearing blue jeans in court.
  The truth is that "Majesty" as a style for kings is not mediaeval.
As EB (11th edition) relates:
  'The term "majesty" was strictly confined in the middle ages to the suc-
cessors of the Roman emperors in the West, and at the treaty of Cambrai 
(1529) it is reserved for the emperor Charles V."
Its adoption by kings dates from the 16th century, when they mystique
of THE Empire was wearing off, and every Tom, Sebastian and Harry started
claiming imperial status.
  In England, for instance, it was taken by Henry VIII, at the same time
that he declared England a "crown imperial" [contrary to popular fallacy, the
"Imperial State Crown" has nothing to do with the Indian Empire], and changed
his title from "Lord" to "King of Ireland". Previous kings had been
"Grace" or "Highness". Scotland never made the change during its independ-
ent existence. (In MONTROSE, Nigel Tranter has a hilarious scene where the
Duke of Hamilton, holding a Commissioner's audience, demands to be called
"Your Grace"; and to his consternation the Scots nobles decline to call him
by a style which they are accustomed to use only for the King, but announce
that they have no objection to calling him "Your Majesty", which has no such
unfortunate connotations.)
   So, if some King wants to revert to a _mediaeval_ usage, attacking him
for an alleged barbarism simply shows igorance; as did the ad demanding
that Corpora enshrine the Victorian "Prince Consort" in the name of "authenticity".
  Baron Alfgar the Sententious, Virgule Herald, etc., etc.

-- 
