Curiously enough, this debate follows closely the discussion in George Silver's
"Brief Instructions on my Paradoxes of Defense", an Elizabethan fighting manual.
Silver argues that the rapier-fight is of no use to the monarch in the wars and
therefore is mere conceit and vanity.  The only proper fight that a courtier
must learn is those that aid his/her King in the wars - which at least in the
Middle Kingdon rules out all but "heavy weapons".  (Silver wrote about 1595;
his manual jibes closely with many heavy weapon techniques.  Duke Master 
Moonwulf's "Florentine" is described exactly in Silver, who also gives the
counter-strategy :-) ).  

I've never done it, but I've heard that it's been done:  give me my three-
quarter harness and a bastard sword and I suspect that the only fight with
the rapier (of the 17th century variety or later) that would work would be
"Cobb's traverse".

Silver describes a battle between an unarmored Englishman with a two-hand
sword and an Italian with the rapier; the encounter was fatal to the Italian.

Silver's book is reprinted in "Three Elizabethan Fencing Manuals" by Scholar's
Press (? on the press).

As those of you who read the signature will note my interest in this area is
not just academic.  I actually have not made a decision on this issue for the
Middle Kingdom; that would require a wider consultation and much more
discussion and collection of information.  I am looking forward to talking
to some fencers at the War.

