Subject: A tale, to get things rolling


Things have gotten kinda quiet here this past week. In order to do something
about this, let's try to get some story-swapping going. I suppose that it isn't
fair that I ask everyone else for anecdotes without providing some of my own. 
This one was re-told to me recently by Mussttapha, and his version is pretty 
close to mine, so I will guess that this is fairly close to something that 
actually happened.

			    "Vis and the Cliff"

Once upon a time, there was a young prince of the East Kingdom named
Vissevald (hereinafter referred to as "Vis", for ease of writing). And it
came to pass that Vis found himself a member of that elite force known as
The National Guard. And Vis (and his CO) found that he was pretty good at
this stuff. And such was the state of things.

One day, Vis' Guard unit found itself training in the same camp as a unit
of Green Beret recruits. The Green Berets, as such are wont to do, felt that
they were the finest fighting force in all the land. And so, one day, while
passing the time over a bottle of mead, Vis' CO bet the Berets' commander that
his men could attack and destroy the Berets' encampment. Bet a great deal of
money, at that. The Green Beret commander took the offer happily, for he was
certain that such a feat was not possible.

You must understand the lay of the land that the Berets were on. Their
encampment lay at the top of a steep cliff, jutting out into the ocean. There
was only one narrow path up to the encampment, and the Berets had that path
heavily guarded at all times. Since the cliff was tall, and almost vertical,
and their sentries were among the best, they reasoned that none could enter
the camp to destroy it. Here, they did not reckon with Vissevald.

Vis' CO, having made the bet, went back to Vis to tell him about it. Vis
was none too happy about having a plan that centered on him made without
his being consulted, but he eventually consented, on the grounds that he
get a cut of the money wagered. As the bet was for a substantial amount,
the CO agreed happily.

Part one of Vissevald's plan was surprise. The Guard unit would attack with
the dawn. Now, such units *never* wake that early, and Vis knew that the
Berets knew that. Thus, he hoped to take the Berets off-guard with an
early-morning mass attack. This was, of course, the distraction.

Part two was Vis himself. Early that morning, before cockscrow, he set out
to scale the steep cliff. Rubber knife clenched in his teeth, plastic hand
grenades strapped to his belt, he began to climb, foot by slow foot. His
reasoning was that the Berets would not have more than one guard at the
cliff; their entire defense was based upon the fact that the cliff was
unclimbable. He would reach the top of the cliff at the same time that his
distraction hit the front gate, sneak in, plant the granades, then leave.
Simple.

Thus, Vis reached the top of the cliff just as the dawn broke, only to
find the one thing that he hadn't expected: an alert sentry. As he pulled
himself over the top of the cliff, the sentry attacked, and a scuffle
ensued. Both Vis' rubber knife, and the sentry's fake gun were lost in the
struggle. As they separated for breath momentarily, they both began to cast
about for weapons, and each came upon a stout stick.

Vis smiled; after all, he was one of the finest fighters in the land, and
now, he was in his element. He swung a mighty blow --

-- and was blocked. Now puzzled, Vis fell into fighting posture, and began
trading blows with the man before him. Though Vis' blows were skilled and
quick, each was blocked by the mysterious sentry. Occasionally, he would
just slip a blow by, and was told, "Glance".

Finally, after a hard bout, Vis delivered a solid blow to the sentry, who
thought for a minute, then fell over. Vis came up to the man, but before
helping him to his feet, asked, "Where did you learn to fight like that?"

"Atenveldt...", said the sentry.

Vis pondered this for a moment, then said, "When you return to your home
land of Atenveldt, tell them of this battle. For there is no shame in being
defeated by the Crown Prince of the East!"

And so, the lone sentry defeated, Vis snuck into the camp, planted his
bombs, and won the bet. And from that day forward, he carried the certain
knowledge that you can meet allies in spirit in the *damnedest* places.

						-- Justin du Coeur

