	A couple of years ago, in the Barony of Sternfeld, in the Middle,
I and some friends were attending an event in countryside of the Barony.
The Site was wonderful, with a roofed enclosure and the wains parked some
distance away.  A few of us were a mite discomforted by some omminously
LARGE tracks not far from the Tourney, but our hosts reasured us that these
were of no consiquence.
	The day of the tourney went well, with a fine list followed by 
other diversions, one of which was a siege weapon contest.  All was well
until the ground started to shake.
	Then, with a great roar and much belching of smoke and steam, a 
HUGE dragon, with black shiny hide and legs moving so fast that they were 
but a blur, rush out of the woods and thundered past the campsite, following 
the tracks that we had noticed earlier.  So great was its speed that before 
we could grab lance, nock arrow or move the catapults to bear on it it had
passed from our sight, leaving only the stench of its breath.
	Our hosts of Sternfeld took all of this in great peace, though
several of the visitors took alarm.  When asked the Sternfelders merely
waved it off as if it was of no consiquence.
	Indeed, twice more during the evening the dragon (or one of its 
cousins) roared past, but non took the slightest not of our knights and
men at arms, nor any of our fair ladies that were present either.  I think
it just as well, for I doubt that any of our weapons, even the weapons 
throwing 20 lb stones, could have done much to the beast.

