Subject: Fencing and fighting

>>with rattan won't work.  I am interested in fencing, but do not believe
>>that Crown Tourney should ever be a fencing bout.  I believe that rattan
>>fighting represents a far greater part of the time period we all live in
>>and that it is more real than fencing in that historically this form of
>>fighting was around for a much longer period of time than fencing was.
>>-  In service to the East, Robert of Ferness, Seneschal of the Dominion

One of the things that I am noticing lately is that people's definitions of 
what is allowed because of periodness is radically different.  

We often also seem to have decided that because the "SCA" has been doing 
something for a good long time that it becomes legitimate by that reason 
along.

In addition, I see a "multiple-standard" for different types of activity.  
There have been comments about the periodness of plate armor.  There is no 
reason for people to make styles of plate armor that are not period.  There 
are certainly examples of types of plate armor and chain armor etc that come 
from before 1600 that are legitimate AND safe.  Many of our fighters don't 
wear period armor but that's all right with most people.  We use rattan 
weapons for safety reasons.  These have legitimate reasons for being this way, 

The real problem that I see is that we have a number of weapons and fighting 
styles in rattan fighting that just cannot be shown to be period to most 
people.  Many people are using advance modern oriental martial art styles that 
didn't exist until the last two hundred years.  Weapons are frequently more 
employed as katana than broadswords.  Many "halberd" styles are naginata 
based.  This is fine for Master Kobayashi, who has a japanese persona.  
Shields have been specially adapted for SCA combat styles.  We've even 
probably invented a number of totally new techniques not used by others 
anywhere.  The is little evidence in our rattan fighting styles of people 
attempting to be strongly in period.  

Yet people fight voraciously over what style of grip a fencer is using.  I 
have heard that our esteemed Baron here in Carolingia is going to a great deal 
of trouble to measure, weight, and examine period fencing weapons in order to 
be able to accurately replicate them for our use.  I think that this is dandy, 
but if people wanted to use modern foils and fencing techniques the rattan 
fighters and the chivalry should be the last people to complain.  

We have medieval documented materials on war styles and techniques, armor and 
arms (though there is endless debate about what armor and weapons were 
actually used when and where over a large percentage of it).  We have evidence 
of period small tactics and small group combats.  I would be interested in 
seeing some documentation on fighting styles for one-on-one combats in the 
medieval period, because I've never seen it.   I would be much more in favor 
of working rattan fighting as melee groups and whole baronies, with leaders 
being not only reasonably good fighters, but strategists and tacticians as 
well.  I would expect for a person to become king then to be someone who has 
demonstrated the true medieval kingly arts of war.   Not someone who is simply 
the best duelist.  I like the notion of Crown Tournaments becoming real wars.  
Sophia also suggested creating a wargame using medieval tactics and 
strategies, which could be another list ( a real wargame on paper).  A 
different scenario could be created for each tourney.  As such, the high 
person winner combining the dueling and the wargame would become king.  

It was also my experience and impression that many of the older fighters when 
I joined in 78 were using fencing styles with rattan as much as they were 
able.  There seemed to be two major reasons for this.  

1.  The older fighters seem to be mundance fencers often.
2.  Those fighters interested in period documentation could find fencing 
styles for duels (one-on-one), but nonjousting documentation for "real 
medieval knights on foot" was not as evident.  

I also remember when I joined that there were lots of people with ridiculous 
heavy, long, 2-handed bastard swords with large awkward guard pieces that look 
like things you see in medieval armories and textbooks.  They went out of 
fashion even while I was fighting because they weren't particularly as good as 
the faster lighter eastern style swords, and people were more interested in 
winning than in fighting in period, with western medieval styles.  

I also seem to remember that one of the reasons the rapier was invented was to 
deal with nuts in plate armor.  And that in any given area of Europe, plate 
armor was only in style for less than a hundred years, as only a massed unit 
of cavalry in heavy armor was good against rabble armies with pitchforks, and 
a lone "knight" would be pulled down and off in a matter of minutes.  

Well this is enough to give people something to *chew" on for awhile.  I can 
hear the howls on the horizon already from the people who will continue to 
like things just the way they are :-).  That's all right.  

By the way, I (like Master Kobayashi said of himself) often like to play 
devil's advocate.  If you get too upset reading anything I say, remember that 
I probably really sympathize with most people's positions and do not have real
malice towards anyone, not even the political kind.

			-Eduardo Bardi
			-Eddie



