Good Master Kobayashi, I would never throw vegetables at a member
of the chivalry  :-) 

These two "outrageous claims" are actually sound points.  The arguments
for arts kings come up every so often, and have so far always died down
again.  Putting myself at considerable political risk here, I will tell
some truths:  The same guy that came up with the five-fold tourney 
was the one who banned fencing in the West.  His queen wore blue jeans
to court.  He changed the laws of the Order of Precedence and knighted 
a person that 98% of the Chivalry despised.  He didn't want people to
address him as 'your majesty'.  These seem to typify the sort of things 
that many people want to avoid in kings.  The man in question is
a Triple Peer.  Not even Laurels can be counted on to be great kings.
I'm not saying that rattan fighting is and always shall be the best way
to determine a monarch, but just because they can herald, and 
calligraph, and dance, and play chess doesn't guarantee that the winner
would be any "better" as a monarch than Joe Stickjock.  

On the art of rattan fighting in the SCA:
My knight and my squire-brother have been writing down moves, shots,
footwork, feints, etc.  in an attempt to look at fighting in a similar 
way to how other marshal arts are viewed.  Rattan fighting doesn't have
set katas, but the elements of fighting break down in interesting ways.
Have other people tried this sort of thing?  Would others be interested 
in Eric and John's notes?

I must most heartily agree with Master Kobayashi's claims.  It is NOT
true that any dork with a sword can be king.  Once you know what  to
look for, you can tell if a fighter has tight control of his blows, 
good stance, good targeting, and such that make a fight elegant.  
[one of the most beautiful things to watch is a bout between two 
skilled greatswordsmen}  Non-fighters are generally quicker to think
that bogus blows should have been taken.  Shots do glance, and hit tippy
and catch shield, and hit flat.  Come out to a couple fighter practices,
climb inside some armor, and see how accurately you judge blows,
especially when you're new.  Now, I know most of you don't yap about how 
Sir X should have taken that leg shot, but I have heard people,
experienced SCA people, do so.  I hope to be given the benefit of the
doubt when I'm on the field, and I'm careful in extending this courtesy
to others.

Your next potential vegetable target,

