From: ron<%hpfcmr.uucp@hplabs.hp.com>  (Ron Miller)
Subject: Re: sca: fencing blade inspection
Message-Id: <5020001@hpfcmr.HP.COM>

Pardon me, but the discussion looks much like detecting metal flaws.....


An inexpensive method to detect metal cracks is to apply a dye called
Prussian Blue to the metal of interest let it soak for awhile, then 
wipe the PB off with a cloth. Following the wipe, a white powder (like talc)is
applied to the metal. PB absorbed into a crack in the metal will re-emerge
into the white powder and stain the powder. Voila! Indication of 
a crack. 

An alternative method is to use something called  "ultrasonic inspection" 
where a transducer is applied to the metal and a sonar-like process of
transmission and reflection from material boundaries occurs. The 
machine isn't cheap and requires significant training to use properly.
But it can detect subsurface defects.

Yet another technique is called "magnaflux" where a magnetic field is
induced so as to permeate the metal. Iron powder is sprinkled onto the 
metal and the orientation of the iron particles is studied. Discontinuities
such as cracks and voids will have a different magnetic field and thus
a different distribution of iron particles around them.This also can
detect subsurface defects.

And for the ultimate environmental insult, RADIOGRAPHY. Use a radiation
source to "illuminate" the metal. Capture an image on film using the 
radiation source. (This is effectively like medical or dental X-rays).
This will also detect subsurface defects.

For use on small items such as fencing equipment, the Prussian Blue 
method is most practical. (outside of ignoring the problem of course)

The above are standard techniques for metal fabricating trades.
I happened to have learned about it in the Navy.

Happy Fencing!

