From: almond%hustat@harvard.harvard.edu (Russell Almond)
Subject: Fencing Crowns


I have heard a large number of people come down in favour of fencing
as a way of deciding the crown tournaments.  I must respectfully
disagree with them, even though I am a fencer myself.

To begin with, I must say that switching from rattan to fencing as a way of
deciding crowns will cause no improvements.  Rhinohiding is as
potentially as large a problem in both lists, and a "wire-jock" as
crown could be just as disasterous as having a "stick-jock."

Let us look at what is really required of the Monarch.  First Their
Majesties must be able to provide sufficient bread and cirrcuses for
the masses.  Unfortunatly, there is no way to test for this one before
the Monarchs assends the throne.  Secondly, their Majesties must be
able to judge in matters pertaining to all activities going on with
the society, but in particular, with give out awards.  True, Their
Majesties do and should rely heavily on the populace (in particular in
the members of their poling orders) to carry out those duties, but
they need at least a passing familiarity in order to perform those
duties well.

Perhaps we should require that potential Monarchs have a passing
familiarity with the other aspects of life in the Current Middle Ages.
The East Kingdom already requires a residency (of I believe 1 year)
and travelling to a sufficient number of events during that time over
sufficiently diverse locations that Their Most Royal Majesties will
provide bread anc circusses for at least a large portion of the
masses.  We might further go on to require that Their Majesties had
some passing familiarity with the other arts as well.

Thus a typical requirement for entry in the Crown Tourney would be:
For the Monarch 
	1) SCA member
	2) Residency and Travelling
	3) Must practice 1 art or science at a sufficient level to be
able to display his/her at crown Tourney.
	4) Must perform sufficient service to the society that at
least 5 people (2 out of local group) will testify in writing to the
service.
	5) Qualified Fighter (to enter Tourney)
For the Consort
	1-4) above
	5) Either a qualified figher to fencer (i.e., has some
familiarity with the fighting arts) or an extra art/science or extra
service.  

The new reigning Monarch would still be selected by the tourney as
before, it is just that now the Monarch cannot be purely a
"Stick-jock" (or "Wire-jock") as in the other proposals.  This system
is I think both workable and practical, however, I offer it mainly for
the sake of disscussion.

	--Mussttapha
	(almond@hustat.harvard.edu)

If fate throws a knife at you, there are two ways of catching it: by
the blade, and by the handle.

