Date: Wed, 25 May 88 11:57:06 -0400 (EDT)
From: Dani Zweig <haste+@andrew.cmu.edu>
Subject: SCA Bureaucracy

So the new prince of the East isn't -- because he forgot to renew his
membership.  Not very smart, was it?  Of course, he's still a member, but his
membership expires at the end of the month.  And it takes a couple of months to
renew.

Is there any earthly reason it should take more than a few days?  And even if
there is (e.g. the person handling renewals prefers to do several hundred at a
time instead of as they come in) when did we become so inflexibly rule-bound?

I'm not particularly upset over the oversetting of the Crown, but I *don't*
care for the bureaucratization it implies.

We have a local member whose name was rejected, not for inappropriateness or
lack of authenticity, but because it was longer than the number of characters
the SCA database allows for names.  (Yes, it was very long.  What of it?)

The past couple of years have seen an explosion in the volume of reporting
being demanded of local officers by their Kingdom superiors.  Some of the
requested reports make some sort of sense -- others will never be read.

OK.  Let's grant that a society of 10,000 members requires more structure than
a society of 1,000 members.  It's still a case that that structure is there to
serve the membership, and not the other way around.  IT IS A MYTH that a large
bureacracy is necessarily impersonal and unresponsive.  Those are
characteristics not of large bureacracies but of bureaucracies whose members
have no stake in what they do and no incentive to do it well.  That should not
characterize the society.

--Dani of the Seven Wells

