Subject: In Defence of Rattan Fighting

I am Master Kobayashi Yutaka of the East, Seneschal of Carolingia,
and Various Other Things.  The "Master" is for "Master-at-Arms".

I must admit to feeling a bit put upon.  The general impression that
i'm getting is that if all the fighters in the Known World, and everything
associated with them, were suddenly to vanish into a black hole, the
rest of you would breathe a collective sigh of relief, all of your
problems solved.  No more stupid stick jocks on the throne.   No more
boring tourneys.  No more macho braggarts strutting their ignorance
about.

Well, i want to make two outrageous claims on the subject:

Outrageous Claim #1: There is as much art in fighting as there is in
	anything else.

Outrageous Claim #2: If you are not a fighter, you know not whereof you speak.

[pause to dodge vegetable matter flung in my direction.  effort not entirely
successful.]

Let me explain...

Number 1 is actually not that difficult, but people forget so it deserves
mentioning now and again.  If the spectators only cheer the winner, then
that is what the fighter notices.  If the spectators cheer both impartially,
because the bout was well-fought, or the kill was particularly spectacular,
the fighter will notice that as well.  When is the last time you went up to
a fighter and said, "Well-fought.  I enjoyed watching"?

Which brings me to #2.

Nothing will glaze a fighter's eyes faster than some bozo coming up after a
fight and describing "the perfect move" that would have carried the day.  The
description is confusing, and the move itself was gleaned from the most
recent episode of Flying Fists of Death Theatre.  The encounter ends more
or less politely, depending on the individuals, and the fighter's opinions have
not changed one iota.

People feel foolish if they find they've been holding forth on an art and one
of the listeners turns out to be a Laurel in that art.  Why don't fighters
get the same respect in their field?  It's just as ill-defined as many arts
i can think of, has at least as many schools of practice, and is amenable to
the same sort of snobbery.  Why doesn't anyone feel badly when they haven't
bothered to learn *our* jargon-words and we can't understand them, or they
us?  Why do all these people hate us *when they haven't even taken the time to
see what's involved*?  [Whine.  Whine.]

The more one knows about something, the more one can appreciate it.  *Learn*
about fighting, ask questions of fighters, and the tourneys won't be so boring.
As a side effect, when you want to say something to a fighter it will have
more impact, because you will be knowlegeable and be able to convey your idea.

This is already too long.  I have *much* more to say, but would rather
not flood the net with my ravings.

In Service to Who Knows What,

