Greetings unto the knowne world from David Waxthorn, a simple Norman
administrator with a funny name.

I am mundanely a member of the fencing club here at Lehigh, and we do
not participate in electronic tournaments.  The style of fencing
taught here is much more 'nasty' than tournament rules allow -
although we are taught the rules of dry-fencing.  (Please - no USFA
flames.  We view fencing as a martial art, and happily abide by all
USFA rules when fencing others).

One of the first things we are taught is how to break a blade (#2
foil) and stab someone in the throat.  It is simply a hard 2 or 5
extension without turning the wrint over.  The blade tries to bend
along the wrong axis, breaks, and impales your opponent.  The reason
we are told this is that not turning the wrist over is a common
mistake of novices, and fear of causing injury is a great motivator
for correct technique.  Therefore, a blade does not need to be
fatigued or cracked in order to break.

In my experience with SCA fencing, I have used an epee blade.  I have
NEVER used a hack/slash attack - it is too dangerous.  I do, however,
use draw cuts often; therefore, I do not agree that the edge of an
epee should be disallowed.

Fencing should be fun.  It does not matter to me if I win or die -
only if I have enjoyed the duel.  Too many people take this too
seriously, and they are the ones that make it less enjoyable.

