(An aside to Michael Squires--I tried to send you mail but don't know
how to get to Pitt!  Do you have any suggestions on what path may reach
you from INTERNET?)

I think this is a fascinating and legitimate (certainly!) area of
inquiry in the SCA.

The Barony of Carolingia (Boston, Mass., area) runs a University each
year, which is like a combined event and demo--mundanes may attend, and
it is publicized mundanely on a limited scale.  The lecturers are SCA
scholars, who give their lectures in persona.  The topics are strictly
medieval ones (such as astronomy, or the hierarchy of angels.)  This 
comes closer to re-creating the medieval sort of university, than other
types of Schola/University events seem to.  Our yearly Schola event
here in Debateable Lands is run by our College of Cour d'Or, and seems
to be moving in the direction of becoming more authentic, but the
process is necessarily slow.  There is always a need to offer
instruction about the SCA itself, for the benefit of newcomers, and
because it helps us gain some perspective on our organization.

My lord, Magnus, admires the medieval ideal of the itinerant scholar
but has yet to construct a persona around it.

I think this is a fascinating area which is large unplumbed in the SCA.
Are there any groups out there who have tried to re-create university
life?

