	Greetings to you all.  I have fenced mundanely for 4 years and
fenced in the Society for one year and I have seen only 3 accidents in 
that entire time.  1) A bloody nose (mask was too big). 2) A teammate 
didn't wear his cup. 3) A small cut on the back of a teammates neck
from a sabre cut - back of the head protection is a good idea.
	A friend of mine claims to have been at the infamous World Games where
the Russian took one through the mask, she said it was pretty spooky but
accidents happen.  Obviously, we can only take safety so far, but don't 
throw out the baby with the bath water [I always wanted to say that :-)]
Procedures have been developed to determine whether blades and masks are
safe and the marshallate should enforce safety regs concerning conduct on
the field and equipment safety.
	As far as calibration levels go, I have noticed how hard it is
to sometimes get a touch acknowleged.  I don't think I 'RhinoHide' but
when you are in a tourney situation and the adrenalin is racing...
One thing I usually will *not* acknowledge is a slap in lieu of a draw
cut.  It may not be the best way to reduce the chance of getting beaten
to death but you do get your opponents attention concerning the subject.
Luckily its only happened to me once or twice.
	I have noticed that if people are hitting harder I do tend to 
get a little numb, but a lot of time this happens when I work with 
new people, both in mundane and period fencing.  When I was learning
to fence I would have bruises on my body because myself and the other 
novices had no concept of proper fencing distance and we'd sit there
and whale on each other while being way too close.  Proper distance
and footwork will reduce these kinds of injuries and would reduce
calibration levels.  While I am far from being a fencing teacher
the first thing I try to work with new people is proper, classical
footwork  (which is definitely not the way I first learned) and we go
slowly from there.  When I was on the college team, I had hardly any
bruises or injuries, our coach really drilled us in footwork. 
	Consequently, the main reason the Europeans do so much better
than Americans in mundane fencing is their stronger emphasis on 
footwork.

	Here in the East Kingdom, pistol grips will be outlawed in
August.  What is the current status in other kingdoms?  It seems to
me that the marshallate should legislate safety not what is period.

	
