A good intro I recently picked up is: The Medieval Machine -- The Industrial
Revolution of the Middle Ages by Jean Gimpel (Victor Gollancz LTD, London,
1977).  The 10th thru 12th centuries were a period of significant intellectual
ferment.  For example, the eleventh century Archbishop of Canterbury, Saint
Anselm wrote:
        It seems to me negligent, if after we have been confirmed in the
        faith, we do not strive to understand what we believe.

The ideal scientific library of the time (most likely located in Toledo) would
doubtless contain the following  recent (for the time) translations:

  Arabic sources
            Author                      Works
       Al Khwarizmi              Liber Yasgogarum; Alchorismi; Astronomical
                                 Tables ; Algebra
       Rhazes                    De Aluminibus et Salibus
       pseudo-Aristotle          De Proprietatibus Elementorum
       Alhazen                   Opticae Thesaurus
       Avicenna                  Kitab al-Shifa
       Averroe\:s                Commentaries on Aristotle's Works
    Leonardo Fibonacci of Pisa   Liber Abaci (first complete account
                                               of Hindu numerals)
       
  Greek sources
            Author                      Works
        Hippocrates               Aphorisms
        Aristotle                 Meteorologica; Physica; De Caelo et
                                  Mundo; De Generatione et Corruptione;
                                  De Animalibus
        Euclid                    Elements; Optica and Catoptrica
        Archimedes                De Mensura Circuli
        Hero of Alexandria        Pheumatica
        Galen                     various treatises
        Ptolemy                   Almagest; Optica


For mood setting (as well as a preface with interesting pointers) I recommend
James Blish's science fiction work based on the life of Roger Bacon: Doctor 
Mirabilis 

