Subject: sca: fencing blade inspection

>>Inspecting a blade before its use will not give you
>>any hints as to whether the blade is about to break or not.  Blade breaks
>>are almost always completely unexpected.  You cannot *see* metal fatigue
>>(or whatever failure mode it is that causes fencing blades to break,
>>anyone out there know?).

Unexpected?  Well not exactly, one may say, not predictable.  Blade breakage
occures due to fatigue of metal, which the USFA chair of its tech committee
described to me as microscopic cracks develop... these are the points where the
blade will break.  (Yes, the meterials people will also talk of crystalization 
and...)

So to detect these cracks, one may use an experimental sonic device which shows
stress formations within the metal... well that is a bit expensive, and not
readily available to any marshal. :-)

The FIE requires the use of "miraging steel" blades.  This is a treatement
process that resists cracking.  The blades are much more reliable and break
less often... and not usually under dangerous conditions.  IE: The blade will
break in an attempt to straighten it... not in the lunge that actually did the
bending.  These blades are still new and are still undergoing the test of time.

How do you detect metal fatigue?  Well, it is really easy to test 90% of the 
cases.  In a straight blade (you do not even pass "bent" ones... now the person
may have straightened a bend, that may be ok if it passes this following test..)
you simply bend the blade with a gentle thrust against an inanimate object
(floor or a wall works) in excess of what a normal thrust would be... an extream
thrust. Release the tension, if the blade holds a bend, it should be discarded.

What this test shows through "dynamic testing" methods is if the metal has
softened/lost its temper.  Blades that have been "over bent" or retain "s"
curves will fail this test in most cases.

You may notice mundane fencers "jabbing" the blade into the floor after they 
straighten one, this is why...

Yours in Service,

