Date: Fri, 20 May 88 10:37:29 edt
From: deo%huhepl.DECNET@harvard.harvard.edu
Subject: On the choosing of monarchs

First off, some historical facts.

1.  Tournaments, as we know them and recreate them in the SCA, are a 
RENAISSANCE phenomenon, *not* a medieval one.

2.  MOST of our cooking, ALL of our dancing (the earliest dance manuals extant
date from the mid-1400's), and a large chunk of our heraldy and costuming as
seen in the SCA, is RENAISSANCE, *not* medieval.

Considering these facts, and considering the fact that these are the activities
we see the most of in the SCA, how can anyone claim that we are PRIMARILY
a medieval re-creation society?

The BOD notwitstanding, if you go out to the West, you're going to find a lot
of fighters in full, 16th century plate armour.  And if you're in the east,
you are far more likely to find the nobility attending court in Renaissance
garb than you are in medieval garb.  And EVERYWHERE, if they're dancing, they're
doing Renaissance dance.  And probably eating food prepared from Renaissance
cookbooks (since they are the most readily available period sources).

So it's plain silly to claim that we're a primarily medieval recreation 
society.  The simple fact that fencing IS so popular and growing very 
rapidly should make it clear that the Renaissance is a large part of what
we do.

Also, I don't know how anyone can claim that an Arts competition would be
anymore disputable than a heavy-list crown tourney.  Or have you forgotten
the Crown Tourney which placed Gavin I on the eastern throne, which 
caused such controversy that the kingdom was nearly torn apart, and we ended
up with a very large splinter group which, to this day, still bears great
animosity towards the East?  All of this because a finalist in the lists
got called for rhinohiding?

And as for fairness... I have attended 5 or 6 crown torneys, and I have seen
obvious rhinohiding in all but two of them -- and one of them the King felt
bound to warn the fighters that anyone caught rhinohiding would be banned
from the lists for a YEAR!  Fortunately, the rhinohiders never made it to the
finals, but, still, I have heard many stories of people who won crowns
simply because their threshold to pain was higher than anyone else's.

We in the East have had considerable problem with "stick jock" kings -- 
kings who refuse to do their paperwork, do things against the near
unanimous advice of their Curia and polling orders, and start problems which
have taken 3 or 4 reigns afterward to straighten out.

Our present systems is not perfect -- changing it could make it better or 
worse.  

However, if we don't try to change it, we'll NEVER be able to improve it.

Since we have two Kings per year, I'd like to see the system split into
two DIFFERENT crown tourneys.  I'd like to keep the present system for the
selection of the Summer King, since he must be our Commander at the Pennsic
Wars.  Someone who is a good heavylist fighter and is well-known within
the heavy lists will have a better chance of being a strong War King than
a fencer or artists.

However, I'd like to see the Winter King, who has no martial duties and is
more of a courtier than a warrior, be selected by another method -- perhaps
a fencing tourney (since very few people CANNOT fence, if they wish --
it does not require physical strength or a tolerance to pain and bruising,
but rather skill that any may learn) coupled with a competition in dance
and other arts -- chess and heraldry and extemporaneous oratory perhaps.

After all, sometimes the King ended up being he who was best able to 
OUT-THINK his oponents -- not outfight them!

In service to the Society,

Lady Deonora Ridenow, CM, OS

