Date: 20 May 88 10:14 EDT
From: OTZJ%CORNELLA.BITNET@MITVMA.MIT.EDU
Subject: Loaner Armour

Good day;
   The Dominion of Myrkfaelinn has a large supply of armour which is loaned
out to new fighters.  Since we are located on the campus of a major
university we often get several new fighters each semester.  By having a
closet full of loaner stuff, these prospective fighters may try fighting
before they must invest time and money for their own armour.  The loaner
armour policy says that if a fighter wishes to continue fighting they
may use the loaner armour so long as it is unneeded by a newer member.
Older members are expected to acquire personal armour.
   This system seems to work well, but I must say that we also have a full
time armourer in the group who often does repairs to keep the loaner
stuff in good, safe condition.  The armour has come from various sources:
cast-off stuff as fighters get new gear, lost/found unclaimed bits and
pices, armour created specifically for loaner purpose, stuff left behind
by former group members who are no longer active, etc.
   The best thing about loaner armour is that one need not jump into a
large investment before knowing whther to make a commitment.  We have
several helms with various amounts of padding, a very large box of hockey
gloves picked up at yard sales, sevarl gorgets and elbow cops, about 8
sets of metal leg armour, shields, weapons, and sets of carpet body armour, and
two metal coats of plates.
   It seems to be worth any group getting some loaner armour through a purchase
or a workshop.  This semester we did a carpet armour workshop and produced
several set of body armour -- the carpet came from the steps of a frat house
which had discarded it, so the only cost was two evening's worth of work by
maybe 8-12 people.
  -Robert Ferness, Seneschal

