My interest in fencing was spawned just this past January. While mundane
tournament-style fencing indeed has it's merits, it is, in my opinion, rather
unrealistic of the form being replicated. I prefer the style used in the SCA,
because it is hands-down more realistic. Never, if I am in a swordfight with my
life on the line, am I going to move only forwards and backwards. But on to the
more relevant topics: I am appalled to find it forbidden in the West Kingdom.
Safety indeed. Fencing, if conducted properly, is considerably more safe than
heavy weapons. Fencers are required to have 3-4 layers of trigger over their
bodies. This means full legs and arms, as well as chest and torso. You must
wear a hoodthat fully covers the neck region and spills over to the shoulders.
Over this hood, you wear a fencing mask, similiar to the ones used mundanely,
but these have leather laces in the back to hold them on better. You must wear
a strong glove on each hand, covering to the sleeve of your tunic. And lastly,
you must have boots with enforcedtoe and such, as the foot is also a target.
It is impossible to break a bone with the light blades of foils. You can raise
nasty welts, but nothing compared to the clubs used by others. True, if the
fencing tip (a colored plastic bulb over the blunt tip of the blade) were to
snap, the resulting sharp edge could be harmful. However, if you enforce the
inspection of equipment prior to matches, you can usually prevent this. Also,
an observant marshall can tell when there is no longer a red/green/<your 
favourite bright color> tip to your blade. Believe me, if it were that danger-
ous as a sport, world-wide interest in it would not be so strong (participant-
wise, that is).

