Date: 20 May 88 22:37:53 GMT
From: daver@amdcad.uucp  (Dave Rubin)
Subject: period fencing
Message-Id: <21702@amdcad.AMD.COM>

Here in Ansteorra period fencing is very, very popular.
It has been around for a while then Don Tivar Moondragon
and many others (especially in Austin) codified it and
regulated it. At the last Queen's Champion, which is
the largest light weapons tourney, there were upwards
of 80 fighter I believe. Living about an hour from Austin
which is a real hotbed of period fencing we get a lot of
exposure here. Let me make some comments.

There are minimum and maximum armor requirements. Min is 4
ounce leather or equivalent over the torso. Equivalent is
often four layers of trigger cloth. The test for equivalency
is to punch test the material 4 times with a broken foil and
have no penetration. This is usually done with the material
on the ground. Maximum is as follows (quote from the
Ansteorra rules of the lists) "Any armor that prevents a
duellist from calling a blow or drawcut shall be barred from
use".  Duello is another term for period fencing. To gloss
over the remaining requirements: no bare skin, cup (holes 
plugged), mask, back of head, and armpit protection. These
are more detailed than I put here.
     Only a #5 french foil is used. Epees were used for a while
but have been discontinued (I don't know why). There has
been a lot of research done recently on force of blows 
required including some work with cadavers. The basic 
premise of requiring a blow of sufficient force to make the
blade bend at least 2 inches has been found to be consistant with
real world experiences. Draw cuts are being acknowledged as well.
     Accomplished duellists can become Dons (or Donas ??) which
is the fencing equivalent to a knight. This is not a peerage but
is I believe one tier down. (I know this is a poor way to look
at SCA awards, but....). Dons wear white scarves and may take
cadets who wear red scarves.
     With respect to chivalry, most of the period fencers here
are trying to fight from a question of honor rather than as street
brawlers. Some lists are run where you draw an opponent by random
and there is assumed to be a question of honor between you. At this
point the match is arranged by seconds and the bout is an honorable
(albeit deadly) one. Many fighters will change hands if they hit
your sword hand forcing you to change, and many will go to their
knees if you lose your legs.	
    The major safety question (and really the only one of
significance that I see) is broken blades. I have seen two broken
blades and both times the armor was completely sufficient to stop
the blow. Blades that become kinked or get an 'S' curve are
discarded. As long as masks, throat/neck protection, and torso
armor is well regulated I see very few problems. And this is from
a die-hard heavy fighter who would rather get a broken bone than 
pierced by a foil. However the times I have fenced I have felt
fairly safe.
     The Ansteorran Rapier Marshall is:
	      Don Blayne atteWood the Juggler
	      (James Barnes) (512) 371-0900
Don Tivar, the Society Rapier Marshall, is a good source as well.
Unfortunately I don't have his number handy. The fencers try to make
it to Pennsic every year to 'spread the word' and make Don's from
other places. I assume only a Don can make a Don (or the crown can 
probably do it as well). I will hopefully be attending the Academy
of the Rapier in June which is an Ansteorran event to teach period 
fencing. If I get any good material I will try to condense it to 
the net. Please e-mail me if you want more info, I am new to this
but as K.M. of my barony I am learning and have some good resources
handy. 
			 Robyn Solarius
			 Dave Rubin
P.S. Anyone want to comment on Shinai? We do a little here and this
can be an elegant substitue for period fencing if you wish to fight
light but retain the idea of slashing swords instead of thrusting.

